[White "Introduction"]
[Black "About the Author"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6 {Alright folks, I am getting a bit emotional as I am writing this intro because it means our Caro-Kann project is finally coming to an end. This is the second biggest project that I ever did, after my London System course, and I couldn't be more thankful to everyone that has followed me so far on this crazy journey.What you are about to find in this course is the result of years of work with Grandmaster Constantin Lupulescu, who immediately identified how bad my Najdorf Sicilian really was and made me a true pioneer of the Caro-Kann Defense. I used this opening to achieve the most important milestone of my career (becoming Romanian champion under 18 after a last round must win game, where I used the Caro-Kann defense against a FIDE master). This is still something I never dreamed of as a child who started professional chess relatively late (around 10 years old).Of course, this opening was a great contribution towards achieving my International Master norms, which took almost 5 years since I achieved the FIDE master title at the age of 15. Once I finally got the IM title after 5 years of hard work and travelling around the world, I decided to take a step back from professional chess and try to make videos on the internet (since streaming started to pick up among chess players).A lot of viewers wonder if I will ever make a comeback into professional chess and try to pursue the Grandmaster title, so I figured I'll just answer that here. The Grandmaster title is something truly unique, but sadly the reward is almost non-existent financially. In order to make any serious income from playing chess you have to be among the best 50 players in the world (which in my opinion athletes that make it to that level are simply born for it with some unique talent). I clearly do not fit in that category, but I am here to learn from those people and share my thoughts with you. After all... You never know who's going to be the next Magnus Carlsen!So far, in the three years that I fully retired from playing OTB chess I coached dozens of players from all levels between 1000-2000 elo. At first, I have to be honest... It was really a struggle! Coming in from the professional scene to explain basic ideas to people that have a hard time even identifying squares of the board was a big change. Almost none of the mainline theory applies, they get hit by all sorts of 'random' moves that makes it really discouraging for the newer players. At the end of the day, what's the point of learning openings if they never enter those theoretical lines anyways?So in order to solve this problem, I had to come up with a repertoire that contains very little move by move stuff, restricts options for the opponent, has clear middlegame ideas, and even a cactus could play it! This way the London System+Caro-Kann Defense combo was born.Now, to sum up this long boring introduction, this course contains all the important main lines that a professional players needs to know at about 2400 FIDE level + a deep dive into beginners mind (which I think is really the special sauce of this course).} 
