[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Structure of the Repertoire"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6 {This course is very light on trainables because I specifically picked lines that can transpose into each other, cutting a lot of the nonsense. Here you have a clear structure of what the course is based on:• Classical Variation (1...c62.d4d53.Nc3dxe44.Nxe4Nf65.Nxf6+exf66.c3Bd67.Bd3O-O8.Qc2Re8+9.Ne2h6) ➼ This is an important deviation, as all the recent repertoires have gone for the more computer-ish approach with9...h5where it can become tricky to defend that h-pawn when White castles short.• Two Knights (1...c62.Nc3d53.Nf3dxe44.Nxe4Nf65.Qe2Nxe46.Qxe4Be6) ➼ Another innovative approach which recently started to gain a lot of followers, staying away from the more popular6...Qa5and6...Nd7.Exchange Variation (1...c62.d4d53.exd5cxd54.Bd3Nf65.c3Bg46.Qb3Qc7) ➼ This variation is still somewhat in its early days, but it's clearly the choice of the biggest Caro-Kann experts such as Firouzja and Keymer.• Panov Attack (1...c62.d4d53.exd5cxd54.c4Nf65.Nc3e6) ➼ This is the most practical approach in my opinion, because most casual players will have a hard time remembering the forced draw arising after5...Nc66.Nf3Bg47.cxd5Nxd58.Qb3(why not try to beat the Panov?).• Fantasy Variation (1...c62.d4d53.f3e5) ➼ I don't care that this variation is slightly dubious at the master level, because below 2000 it is simply unstoppable. Give this course some rubies in case you get a quick checkmate!• King's Indian Attack (1...c62.d3g6) ➼ Once again we take the less explored path because I find these positions easier to play compared to the well established main lines starting with2...e5.The modern Tabia (1...c62.Nf3d53.d3g6) ➼ Creating a nice synergy with our repertoire against the KIA, while also going for a really hard counter to White's strategy. In my opinion, White is very happy entering the endgame where the position is equal, but they have more experience and can maneuver around.• Advance Variation (1...c62.d4d53.e5c5) ➼ This part will be split between two chapters:• Sidelines (4.c3&4.Nf3)• Mainlines (4.dxc5Nc6). Although4...Nc6is a bit inferior to4...e6objectively speaking, I find the4...Nc6linesmuch more practical below 2000 and even for my own games around 2600-2700 chess.com Blitz, I get very comfortable positions against Grandmasters on a regular basis (my nickname is 'Banzeus' in case you want to stalk me).} 
