[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. exd5 {This is the traditional way of reaching the Exchange Variation. The important thing to know about this is that by learning the mainlines you will automatically have a very solid understanding which will also apply against the sidelines.For example, in lower rated games it is very common that White will start with move orders such as1.e4c62.Nf3d53.exd5or1.e4c62.Nc3d53.exd5or even1.e4c62.Bc4d53.exd5, which all can be placed into the same bucket of the 'Exchange Variation'. What I love about the Caro-Kann the most is that we can easily predict our opponent's moves, making it super easy to adapt.} 
3. cxd5
4. Nf3 {This could be dangerous if White combines it with Ne5 on the very next move. However, most players below 2000 online rating will not be aware of that plan and generally just get an inferior version of the 'Exchange Variation'.} 
4. Nc6 {Since we are no longer in a rush with the concrete ...Nf6-Bg4 as we are against 4.Bd3, we can start with 4...Nc6 because it already takes the e5-square under control.} 
5. Nc3 {This poor move is incredibly common for lower rated players below 1500 online. The knight simply does not fit well on the c3-square in this 'Carlsbad structure'. It is like a penguin trying to climb a tree ➼ it's out of its element and struggling to find its footing in a place where it just doesn't belong.} 
5. Bg4 {Pinning the knight and preparing to play ...e6 followed by ...Bd6!} 
6. Bb5 {This is super common below 1500.} 
6. e6
7. h3
7. Bxf3 {We always meet h3 with ...Bxf3 in the 'Exchange Variation' when White has played Bb5, because7...Bh5allows8.g4Bg69.Ne5which can be very dangerous.} 
8. Qxf3
8. Nf6
9. Bg5
9. Be7 {Making sure that Bxf6 is never a problem.} 
10. O-O {This is a bit more common than castling long, but you'd be surprised how many people go10.O-O-Oas well!} 
10. O-O {After this move, we have unpinned the c6-knight, so ...Nxd4 becomes a huge threat which a lot of lower rated players tend to forget about!If you want to be ultra precise, you can also throw in10...Rc8so you can take back with THE ROOK.} 
11. Rad1
11. Rc8 {We are going to play on the queenside with ...a6-b5 followed by ...Na5-Nc4 ideas. In case of Bxc6 we always recapture with the rook if possible!} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Panov with 7.Bd3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. exd5
3. cxd5
4. c4 {This is the traditional way of playing the Panov Attack. White's position is pretty easy to play, but besides that there are not too many positive aspects! Black has many ways to equalise + some newer lines in order to try and outplay White.However, in this repertoire we will be going over what I find to be the easiest set-up to play where you basically only need to know where our pieces belong. After that, you should have a completely fine position, which you can use to try and play for a win later on in the game.} 
4. Nf6
5. Nc3
5. e6 {This move may seem a bit ugly at first, but it is actually not that bad and it will keep us pretty safe.The main idea that is important to understand is simply that chess is a reactive game! We can compare it with tennis, because in both games you need to react to what your opponent does. In this case because they have played c4, which completely justifies the ...e6 move, because it makes Black's center feel pretty solid.One key detail that lower rated players often fail to understand is that our light-squared bishop will not be blocked for the rest of the game, but we have ideas to go ...dxc4 (once White develops the light-squared bishop) followed by ...b6-Bb7, occupying the monster diagonal.While there is nothing wrong with entering the variation arising after5...Nc66.Nf3Bg4, I personally simply dislike having to learn 20 moves of theory just to enter a drawish endgame (mess up one move and you can easily get a losing position).Another decent option is5...g6, but once again I feel like we are over-complicating things with this approach.Before we move on there is one last important detail: the move order does matter! Playing5...Nc6?!is a mistake from our point of view, because after6.Nf3e67.c5!White is slightly better. The right way of entering these ...e6 lines is5...e6!, which I will explain later.} 
6. Nf3 {This is the most popular move. White does not really have many alternatives besides6.c5(other moves will most likely transpose).} 
6. Be7 {Once again, in my opinion this is the simplest move.There is nothing wrong with6...Bb4from a theoretical perspective, but giving up the bishop pair is not a very obvious decision and it can easily get us in trouble. Intellectuals solve problems, while geniuses prevent them. You get the point!Now after6...Be7White has a choice between:  •7.cxd5(the main line);  •7.Bd3(very common online);  •7.c5.} 
7. Bd3 {This is the second most common move, or if you think about the fact that7.Be2leads to the same thing ➼ it is actually the most common variation overall!} 
7. dxc4 {Entering the IQP position in an ideal way (waiting for White to lose a tempo first by developing their light-squared bishop).} 
8. Bxc4
8. O-O
9. O-O
9. Nc6 {This is the best square for the knight because it puts pressure on the d4-pawn while preparing future maneuvers such as ...Nb4-Nd5 or ...Na5-Nc4 (after ...b6-Bb7-Rc8).} 
10. Re1
10. b6 {This is the key move to solve the issue of our light-squared bishop. From b7, the bishop will have no rival on the long diagonal!} 
11. Bg5 {This is the most common developing move for White.} 
11. Bb7
12. Rc1
12. Rc8 {What I really love about this variation is the fact that you can simply remember the final position and this will make it incredibly easy to figure out how to play the opening, in case you have a hard time memorizing variations. Focus on what the pawn structure looks like and where each piece belongs, and my friends, you have the reciepe for succes!From now on, we can continue with a typical maneuver such as ...Nb4-Nbd5 with a very solid position. The general strategy is to exchange pieces, and as long as White does not get any attack against our king ➼ Black is slightly better in the endgames by default (thanks to the better pawn structure).} 
