[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Advance Variation Sidelines"]
[Black "Advance Variation Sidelines: Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. e5 {This is the starting position for the Advance Variation. Here it's important to remember that we want to undermine White's center!} 
3. c5 {A direct attempt to destroy White's center after ...cxd4! Now the most critical reply for White is4.dxc5, but in this chapter we will be dealing with everything but that!} 
4. c3 {This is the most common move below 2200 and what you are going to face about 50% of your games.4.Nf3This will typically transpose into either 4.c3 lines or 4.dxc5.4...Nc65.c4This is the only variation with some independent value.5...cxd46.Nxd4e6!This is the important move to remember in order to 'stop the bleeding' in the center. For more details check out the trainables!} 
4. Nc6
5. Nf3 {5.Bb5Creating a massive threat of dxc5! This is definitely something to seriously keep in mind because most of my students tend to forget about Black's key move to get a good game.5...Qa5!Immediately putting the b5-bishop under pressure while creating a positional threat of ...cxd4, as the queen is preventing the ideal way for White to recapture the pawn on d4 due to the pin along the a5-e1 diagonal.5.Be3cxd46.cxd4Bf5=We are going to continue with ... e6-Nge7 and Black has a fine position.5.f4cxd46.cxd4Bf5Sticking with the simplest move, even though 6...h5 is also interesting if you can remember it!5.Be2This was given by Anish Giri in his beautiful 1.e4 Lifetime Repertoire.5...cxd46.cxd4Bf5Keeping our simple back-up strategy in all these lines where White avoid the ...Bg4 pin.5.dxc5Nxe5=With an equal game where it's important to understand that our dark-squared bishop is optimally placed on the a1-h8 diagonal.} 
5. cxd4 {The timing is pretty important, but5...Bg4is not the biggest mistake of all time. in our worst case scenario White has6.dxc5, transposing to the 4.dxc5 lines of the next chapter!} 
6. cxd4
6. Bg4 {Black is simply getting an improved version of the French Defense because we have no bad light-squared bishop.} 
7. Be2 {7.Bb5In case you are worried about these types of moves, don't worry! I've got you covered so make sure to check out the trainable on this move.} 
7. e6 {We can continue with ...Nge7-Nf5 followed by ... Be7 and ...O-O, while h3 is always going to be met by ...Bxf3! The whole strategy in this structure is to play around the d4-pawn, which from my experience you are generally just going to win it with such ease like stealing a candy from a baby (especially if you are below 1500).} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Advance Variation Sidelines"]
[Black "4.c3 Nc6 5.Nf3 with 7.Be2 & 9.Bg5"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. e5 {This is the starting position of the 'Advance Variation' ➼ the choice of anyone who wants to be at least semi-ambitious when it comes to the opening battle. From my experience this variation is usually the main pain point for most of the people I've worked with, so hey, you are not alone!Before explaining the position, it's important to understand that Black has two main options:•3...Bf5➼ which is the main choice in Grandmaster games. This move will not be covered in the course, but if you are above 2200 FIDE rating, I would seriously consider this option because it will pay off in the long run. The 'problem' with this variation is that it really requires a lot of knowledge, and usually forgetting a move can get you in trouble big time.•3...c5(The Botvinnik-Carls Defense) ➼ which is our main line in this course! From a theoretical perspective, this variation is completely fine, but will sometimes require us to lock the light squared bishop inside the pawn chain by playing ...e6 (with positions that are typical for the French Defense).Understanding when/how to play with the passive light-squared bishop is the real challenge when going for3...c5, but the good news is that if you are playing the Caro-Kann below 2200, literally nobody will have a proper understanding of these positions ➼ often going for harmless lines that are very easy to play for Black with little to no theoretical knowledge about the opening.What I really love about this specific line is that most of the times you can get away with simply understanding the pawn structure & remembering where each piece should be placed.} 
3. c5 {After this move the wide player pool will react the following way:  •4.c3(50%)  •4.dxc5(20%)  •4.Nf3(20%)   • and the rest are super rare.From a theoretical perspective, the most dangerous move is known to be4.dxc5, ➼ referred to by many as the only way to play for an advantage. Personally I consider this move to be the biggest 'memory test' for Black, as the lines should be completely harmless.Recently, top level Grandmasters have even started to switch on to the 'let's get a fresh position' approach by going4.Nf3, which is an indication that4.dxc5is no longer considered to be problematic for Black.} 
4. c3 {This is what you are going to face in most of your games. While there are a few interesting ways for White to play this variation, from my experience ➼ this is a sign that your opponent is completely clueless and just tries to get a 'playable' position. You can think of this as the student who parties all night, but still decides to show up at the exam, just in case by a miracle they will pass (I would never do that, of course!).Against solid play, Black will generally get at least an equal position, while if you are playing this below 1500 blitz, my students are usually just winning the d4-pawn sooner or later with a completely winning position from the opening (watch out for that!).} 
4. Nc6 {Developing the knight onto its natural square while pressuring the main point of the battle ➼ the d4-square. For trainables we have5.Nf3,5.Bb5and5.Be2, but besides that I will mention all the other rare alternatives in the 5.Ne2 trainable. The good news is that generally if you understand the structure arising after5.Nf3, the rest will be very similar and you should be able to figure it out on your own during the game.} 
5. Nf3 {This is by far the most common move for White, leading to an easy game for us.} 
5. cxd4 {This is the most precise, because the immediate5...Bg46.dxc5!would transpose to a stronger line for White which is covered via the 4.dxc5 move order. This is one of the most common inaccuracies that I see among my students, but generally White is not going to find the transposition.} 
6. cxd4
6. Bg4 {Here you can see the main advantage of the 3...c5 line! Black is able to develop the bishop all the way to g4 (instead of 3...Bf5) ➼ which puts tremendous pressure on White's center (we are already threatening ...Bxf3 when White is unable to take back with the queen in view of ...Nxd4).You can already stop with the theory here and just remember that Black wants to finish development by playing ...e6-Nge7-Nf5 followed by ...Be7 and ...O-O with an easy position to play (we always meet h3 with ...Bxf3 in the 'Advance Variation').Now, of course, if you want to take your knowledge to the next level, the following details that I am about to show will definitely help you exploit the average opponent, but as someone below 1500 blitz, this should already be a pretty solid starting point.} 
7. Be2 {This is by far the most common move.7.Bb5is an important alternative for White which is covered in a different trainable, while7.h3is a typical mistake allowing7...Bxf3!forcing White to play8.gxf3(to avoid losing the d4-pawn) and Black is much better strategically speaking because of the ruined structure on the kingside.White's rare 7th move alternatives are covered in the 7.Qb3 trainable.} 
7. e6
8. O-O {This is the most common move. We always meet8.h3with...Bxf3in the 'Advance Variation', while8.Bg5?Qb6!usually leads to a completely winning position for Black after9.b3?Bxf3!10.Bxf3Qxd4!forcing the queens off with a winning endgame.} 
8. Nge7 {I want to make it very clear that we are specifically playing this move because of the annoying e5-pawn that is stopping the natural ...Nf6 move. A common mistake that I see is that a lot of the lower rated players first learn the 'Advance Variation', and then they keep developing the same way in other variations with ...Nge7-Nf5 even when White does not have a pawn on e5. In the Caro-Kann, if possible, we generally develop our knights to their natural squares (f6 and c6).} 
9. Bg5 {A common move for lower rated games.} 
 {We can meet this in the standard way to unpin with} 9. Qb6 {Usually this just leads to a free win for Black.} 
10. b3
10. Bxf3 {Removing the defender of the d4-pawn.} 
11. Bxf3
11. Qxd4 {This forces a winning endgame for Black.} 
