5. Nf3 {This is by far the most common move for White, leading to an easy game for us.} 
5. cxd4 {This is the most precise, because the immediate5...Bg46.dxc5!would transpose to a stronger line for White which is covered via the 4.dxc5 move order. This is one of the most common inaccuracies that I see among my students, but generally White is not going to find the transposition.} 
6. cxd4
6. Bg4 {Here you can see the main advantage of the 3...c5 line! Black is able to develop the bishop all the way to g4 (instead of 3...Bf5) ➼ which puts tremendous pressure on White's center (we are already threatening ...Bxf3 when White is unable to take back with the queen in view of ...Nxd4).You can already stop with the theory here and just remember that Black wants to finish development by playing ...e6-Nge7-Nf5 followed by ...Be7 and ...O-O with an easy position to play (we always meet h3 with ...Bxf3 in the 'Advance Variation').Now, of course, if you want to take your knowledge to the next level, the following details that I am about to show will definitely help you exploit the average opponent, but as someone below 1500 blitz, this should already be a pretty solid starting point.} 
7. Be2 {This is by far the most common move.7.Bb5is an important alternative for White which is covered in a different trainable, while7.h3is a typical mistake allowing7...Bxf3!forcing White to play8.gxf3(to avoid losing the d4-pawn) and Black is much better strategically speaking because of the ruined structure on the kingside.White's rare 7th move alternatives are covered in the 7.Qb3 trainable.} 
7. e6
8. O-O {This is the most common move. We always meet8.h3with...Bxf3in the 'Advance Variation', while8.Bg5?Qb6!usually leads to a completely winning position for Black after9.b3?Bxf3!10.Bxf3Qxd4!forcing the queens off with a winning endgame.} 
8. Nge7 {I want to make it very clear that we are specifically playing this move because of the annoying e5-pawn that is stopping the natural ...Nf6 move. A common mistake that I see is that a lot of the lower rated players first learn the 'Advance Variation', and then they keep developing the same way in other variations with ...Nge7-Nf5 even when White does not have a pawn on e5. In the Caro-Kann, if possible, we generally develop our knights to their natural squares (f6 and c6).} 
9. Nc3 {Going for natural development.9.Be3This generally won't change much, but it gives White an alternative to play with Nbd2!?9...Nf510.Nbd2This is an interesting idea so that White can recapture with the knight on f3.10...Be711.h3Bxf3In this ultra specific moment the computer likes 11...Bh5 too, but I would just stick with the simple 'always take on f3 against the Advance'.12.Nxf3O-O13.Bd3Threatening to double the pawns with Bxf5!13...Nxe314.fxe3Rc815.Rc1g6Blunting the d3-bishop.16.a3f617.exf6Bxf6=With a pretty dull position. Of course, Black has nothing to worry about.} 
9. Nf5 {Creating a big threat of ...Bxf3 followed by ...Nxd4! Now a common mistake for White is10.h3?Bxf3!11.Bxf3Nfxd4with an extra pawn for Black.} 
10. Be3
10. Be7 {Simply preparing to finish development with ...O-O! A typical mistake is10...Nxe3?!because this releases the tension while improving White's position. A simple rule in order to understand when to play ...Nxe3 is the following: we keep the knight on f5 until White attacks it with moves such as g4/Bg4/Bd3.} 
11. h3 {This move will be played sooner or later.} 
11. Bxf3 {We always take on f3 against the 'Advance Variation'. Please keep in mind that we ONLY take on f3 after White spends a tempo on h3. A common mistake among lower rated players is to play ...Bxf3 unprovoked (which is not a disaster, but most of the time it loses a tempo).} 
12. Bxf3
12. O-O
13. a3 {This move and13.Rc1are the two most common plans for White (and they most likely transpose into one another). White wants to expand on the queenside with Rc1-b4 followed by Na4-Nc5 ideas with pressure on the queenside. To me it's mind-blowing that most black players are struggling in these types of positions, knowing the true potential of our position. My goal with this course is to give you a huge win rate in this specific structure!Let's look at some alternatives for White:A)13.Bg4This is the second most common move for White ➼ Creating a positional threat of Bxf5!13...Nxe3Remember the key rule: we only take on e3 when White is threatening the f5-knight!14.fxe3Bg5Attacking the e3-pawn.In case of15.Qf3the reply15...g6!is quite strong, because we are threatening to trap the bishop with ...h5!15.Qe2g6Preparing to push ...h5! The computer is a huge fan of this idea to grab space and then break with ...f6!16.Nb5h517.Bf3f618.exf6Bxf6=We are going to kick the enemy knight with ...a6 followed by ...Qd6 and White is quite vulnerable on the dark squares.B)13.g4Nxe314.fxe3Rc815.Rc1Bg516.Qd2Ne7⩱We can continue with ...Ng6-Nh4 and White's kingside is vulnerable.C)13.Qd2This specific line does not have great theoretical value, but it sets up a nasty trap that we need to be aware of.13...Rc814.Rac1g6=We can break with ...f6 next and Black has good pressure in the center. It's important to stay away from the tempting14...Na515.Nxd5!and White wins a pawn.D)13.Qd3Best, but rare.The main point is that if Black is careless by playing13...Qb6, then14.Nxd5!is a cold shower!13...g614.Bg4Nxe3!Remember that we only take on e3 when the f5-knight is being threatened.15.fxe3Kg716.Rad1Rc8=with a safe position for Black. We can grab space on the kingside with ...h5 followed by the ...f6-break. However, Black can also focus on the typical queenside play with ...a6-b5 followed by ...Na5-Nc4 ideas.} 
13. Rc8 {This move is usually neglected by the lower rated players, who instead prefer to play13...Qb6which can lead to a pretty awkward position after14.Na4!as White is gaining time with their plan on the queenside. Placing our rook on the open file is always useful and shows a solid understanding of the fundamentals of development. We can already stop with the theory here, but going over a few more moves could literally give you a winning position right away.} 
14. Rc1 {Preparing to play b4 followed by Na4-Nc5.A common mistake in this position is14.b4?!allowing14...Nxe5!and Black is already getting rewarded for playing ...Rc8! The game could continue with15.dxe5Rxc316.Bxa7?where a lot of my students tend to overlook16...b6!and the enemy bishop is getting trapped.} 
14. Bg5 {This is the key idea that literally everyone is overlooking. The main reason for that in my opinion is that the Black players are usually married to this idea of playing ...Qb6 which in some positions should be okay, but in this particular case only makes White's idea of Na4 even stronger.} 
15. Bxg5 {This is the most natural move and what I usually face in my games.15.Qd3!This is quite rare, but the best move for White. Now we need to watch out for Nxd5 ideas!15...g6⩱Making sure the f5-knight is well protected against Nxd5 tricks. Black has a solid position. We can continue with ...Kg7 followed by ...a6-b5 and ...Na5-Nc4 ideas on the queenside.15.Re1??Ncxd4-+Simply winning a pawn because16.Bxd4Bxc117.Qxc1Nxd4leads to an extra exchange for Black.15.Qd2?Bxe316.fxe3Qg5!The key move to get a winning position. Black is creating a double attack!17.Rfe1Ncxd4-+With a completely winning position for Black.} 
15. Qxg5
16. Ne2 {This is a very easy position to get. Suddenly... Black is completely winning!} 
16. Ncxd4 {Simply winning a pawn. The main issue is that most players won't even expect Black to be crushing here... Therefore they are likely to miss this idea!} 
17. Nxd4
17. Nxd4
18. Rxc8 {18.Qxd4Rxc1-+wins the exchange.} 
18. Nxf3+ {The key intermediate move.} 
19. Qxf3
19. Rxc8 {With a completely winning endgame for Black thanks to the extra pawn.} 
