6. Bg4 {Here you can see the main advantage of the 3...c5 line! Black is able to develop the bishop all the way to g4 (instead of 3...Bf5) ➼ which puts tremendous pressure on White's center (we are already threatening ...Bxf3 when White is unable to take back with the queen in view of ...Nxd4).You can already stop with the theory here and just remember that Black wants to finish development by playing ...e6-Nge7-Nf5 followed by ...Be7 and ...O-O with an easy position to play (we always meet h3 with ...Bxf3 in the 'Advance Variation').Now, of course, if you want to take your knowledge to the next level, the following details that I am about to show will definitely help you exploit the average opponent, but as someone below 1500 blitz, this should already be a pretty solid starting point.} 
7. Qb3 {This move is quite rare, but leads to an unusual position, therefore I think it's nice to be aware of it at least!Two other rare alternatives are:A)7.Bg5Bxf3!This is always the best move when White is forced to recapture with the pawn.8.gxf3Qb6Attacking both d4 and b2 while sidestepping the d8-h4 diagonal so we can play ...e6 and finish development.9.Nc3e6⩱We can continue with ...Bb4 followed by ...Nge7 and ...O-O with a long term advantage for Black because of the ruined kingside structure.B)7.Nbd2This line is not critical at all, but it's important not to fall for the 'poisoned d4-pawn'.7...e6!Keeping it simple.The greedy7...Nxd4?is a well-known mistake, allowing8.Nxd4!Bxd19.Bb5+and White regains the queen while keeping an extra piece.8.h3Bxf3Whenever White has played Nbd2 and can recapture with the knight on f3 ➼ you always have the option of playing ...Bh5, but I would keep it simple by always taking on f3 againt the 'Advance Variation'.9.Nxf3Bb4+!Forcing trades makes Black's position easier.10.Bd2Bxd2+11.Qxd2Nge712.Bd3Qa5=With a balanced endgame.} 
7. Bxf3
8. gxf3 {This variation is a bit complicated, but I think it's definitely worth entering because Black has an advantage.8.Qxb7This may look scary at first, but the solution is pretty simple.8...Qc8!9.Qxc8+White has to go for this, because9.Ba6Bg4!is just completely winning for Black.9...Rxc810.gxf3Nxd4⩱With a better endgame for Black.} 
8. Nxd4
9. Qxb7
9. e6 {Allowing Bb5+ because the upcoming positions are good for us.9...Rb8?!This move looks quite tempting, connected with ...Nc2+ ideas, but surprisingly, White is better in that line!10.Qxa7Nc2+?!11.Kd1Nxa112.Nc3±With pressure for White because Bb5+ is very annoying.} 
10. Bb5+ {10.Be3Rb8!This move is important against Bb5+ ideas.11.Qa6Nxf3+!Playing it safe! Going after the rook is dangerous because of Bb5+ ideas.12.Kd1Nxe513.Bb5+Nd7⩱The knight is our MVP! Back in time to defend against the annoying check. Now Black is much better with an easy position to play. Just go ...Ngf6-Be7 followed by ...O-O!} 
10. Nxb5
11. Qc6+ {This is White's best try. Keep in mind that11...Qd7?12.Qxa8+just wins for White.} 
11. Ke7 {This is a bit ugly, but White has no follow-up!} 
12. Qxb5
12. f6 {We can continue with ...Kf7-Rb8 and ...Ne7-Nf5 ideas with a safe king and a better position because we managed to destroy White's center.} 
