5. Be2 {This is an interesting try for White, but very rare. I don't expect you to face this move very often. The point is, of course, to avoid the quick ...Bg4 lines!} 
5. cxd4 {While the 'life hack'5...a6!?(hoping for6.Nf3Bg4) is still viable, generally you can just stick with the simple approach of ...Bf5 followed by ...Ne7-Nc8.} 
6. cxd4
6. Bf5
7. Nc3 {This is an interesting alternative given by Anish in his 1. e4 Lifetime Repertoire.} 
7. e6
8. Be3
8. Nge7
9. Rc1 {This is a flexible move, keeping open the option to throw the kingside pawns at us.} 
9. a6 {We have to combat the engine boy with his own weapons! The point is to make a useful move, while White sort of has to commit to something.} 
10. h4
10. h6
11. h5
11. Na5 {While White is expanding on the kingside like real estate prices have gone down 50%, we neet to get some counterplay of our own!} 
12. g4
12. Bh7
13. f4
13. Nc4
14. Bxc4
14. dxc4
15. Qf3
15. Qd7
16. Nge2
16. Bd3 {With a pretty crazy position (but which is fine for Black). We can continue with moves such as ...Rd8-Nd5 and then perhaps break with ...f5!} 
