5. Be3 {This move could throw off a lot of the newer players, but the good news is that you will generally face it in about 1 out of 15 games. The annoying part is that we are unable to get the typical ...Bg4 pin.} 
5. cxd4 {This is the easiest way to play if you don't want to rely on too much concrete memorization.The best move objectively is of course5...Nh6!, as recommended by Sielecki. My personal weapon that I like to use against lower rated players in these types of scenarios where ...Bg4 is not available yet, is5...a6!?which most likely is answered by6.Nf3, allowing us to get back into familiar teritory after6...Bg4!However, the small drawback with that approach is that the game becomes pretty complicated if White does not rush to play Nf3.Therefore, I recommend you stick with the move5...cxd4for safety reasons.} 
6. cxd4
