5. dxc5 {This is quite rare, but it could become tricky if you do not fully understand the structure, so I feel like it's very useful to scratch the surface on this move.} 
5. Nxe5 {Now White has a bunch of random moves to choose from. The main thing to remember is that if possible, we are trying to play ...g6-Bg7 which makes White's queenside storm with b4 less effective since it would weaken the c3-pawn.} 
6. Bb5+ {This move could look a bit scary, but there is nothing really backing it up (not more than a couple of active moves). Let's look at some alternatives:A)6.Nf3This is a pretty natural move.6...Nxf3+7.Qxf3g6!This is the idea to remember from this structure. The dark-squared bishop is ideally placed on g7.8.Bb5+Bd79.Bxd7+Qxd710.O-OBg711.Re1Nf612.Be3O-O13.Nd2e5=Black is clearly very comfortable. We can continue with ...Rac8-Rfe8 while White can only play a waiting strategy.B)6.b4g6!7.Bf4Bg78.Nf3Nxf3+9.Qxf3a5↑Black is already taking over the initiative and threatening ...axb4! Here you can clearly notice why g7 is the ideal square for the dark squared bishop.C)6.Bf4Ng67.Bg3e6Threatening to win back the c5-pawn.8.b4Nf69.Nf3Be710.Bd3O-O11.O-Ob6!Once we finish development, you know ...b6 is always the right way to break and get a lot of lines on the queenside. Our pieces simply come back to life after this move (just like a good meal after a long workout).12.cxb6Qxb6=∞We are going to break with ...a5 followed by ...Ba6 and ...Rfc8 with lots of threats on the queenside.} 
6. Bd7
7. Qxd5 {Winning a pawn, FOR NOW...} 
7. Bxb5
8. Qxe5
8. f6 {Getting rid of White's queen so we can push ...e5!} 
9. Qe6
9. Bd7
10. Qe2
10. e5 {Threatening to win back the c5-pawn.} 
11. b4
11. b6 {This is the key idea to undermine White's queenside and get a lot of compensation. It is truly the most important general idea to take away from this repertoire against the 'Advance Variation'.} 
12. cxb6
12. Qxb6 {Without the light-squared bishop, White is super vulnerable to ...Bb5 ideas (not to mention that ...a5 has potential to completely ruin their queenside).} 
