[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Advance Variation Sidelines"]
[Black "4.c3 Nc6 & Rare 5th Moves"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. e5 {This is the starting position of the 'Advance Variation' ➼ the choice of anyone who wants to be at least semi-ambitious when it comes to the opening battle. From my experience this variation is usually the main pain point for most of the people I've worked with, so hey, you are not alone!Before explaining the position, it's important to understand that Black has two main options:•3...Bf5➼ which is the main choice in Grandmaster games. This move will not be covered in the course, but if you are above 2200 FIDE rating, I would seriously consider this option because it will pay off in the long run. The 'problem' with this variation is that it really requires a lot of knowledge, and usually forgetting a move can get you in trouble big time.•3...c5(The Botvinnik-Carls Defense) ➼ which is our main line in this course! From a theoretical perspective, this variation is completely fine, but will sometimes require us to lock the light squared bishop inside the pawn chain by playing ...e6 (with positions that are typical for the French Defense).Understanding when/how to play with the passive light-squared bishop is the real challenge when going for3...c5, but the good news is that if you are playing the Caro-Kann below 2200, literally nobody will have a proper understanding of these positions ➼ often going for harmless lines that are very easy to play for Black with little to no theoretical knowledge about the opening.What I really love about this specific line is that most of the times you can get away with simply understanding the pawn structure & remembering where each piece should be placed.} 
3. c5 {After this move the wide player pool will react the following way:  •4.c3(50%)  •4.dxc5(20%)  •4.Nf3(20%)   • and the rest are super rare.From a theoretical perspective, the most dangerous move is known to be4.dxc5, ➼ referred to by many as the only way to play for an advantage. Personally I consider this move to be the biggest 'memory test' for Black, as the lines should be completely harmless.Recently, top level Grandmasters have even started to switch on to the 'let's get a fresh position' approach by going4.Nf3, which is an indication that4.dxc5is no longer considered to be problematic for Black.} 
4. c3 {This is what you are going to face in most of your games. While there are a few interesting ways for White to play this variation, from my experience ➼ this is a sign that your opponent is completely clueless and just tries to get a 'playable' position. You can think of this as the student who parties all night, but still decides to show up at the exam, just in case by a miracle they will pass (I would never do that, of course!).Against solid play, Black will generally get at least an equal position, while if you are playing this below 1500 blitz, my students are usually just winning the d4-pawn sooner or later with a completely winning position from the opening (watch out for that!).} 
4. Nc6 {Developing the knight onto its natural square while pressuring the main point of the battle ➼ the d4-square. For trainables we have5.Nf3,5.Bb5and5.Be2, but besides that I will mention all the other rare alternatives in the 5.Ne2 trainable. The good news is that generally if you understand the structure arising after5.Nf3, the rest will be very similar and you should be able to figure it out on your own during the game.} 
5. Ne2 {This is generally a transposition from1.e4c62.Ne2d53.e5c54.d4Nc65.c3and should not be underestimated!A)5.h3Getting rid of our main ...Bg4 idea, but neglecting development. Of course, this leads to an equal game where you can just stick with the usual plans.5...Bf5When ...Bg4 is not possible, we stick with ...Bf5 simply so that we are able to play ...e6 without locking the bishop inside the pawn chain.6.Nf3e6If White plays something casual like 7.Be2, we can continue with the standard ...cxd4 followed by ...Nge7-Nc8-Nb6 with ...Be7 and ...O-O and Black has good prospects on the queenside.7.Bb5Qb6!This move works best against Bb5 ➼ gaining a tempo while avoiding the doubled pawns.8.Bxc6+Qxc69.O-Oc4⩱Black is already slightly better thanks to the bishop pair. We can continue with ...Ne7-Ng6 followed by ...Be7 & ...O-O, and ultimately push our queenside pawns with ...b5-a5-b4!B)5.a3!?This is an interesting idea for White, avoiding the ...Bg4 lines while potentially going for queenside play with b4.5...Bf5Sticking with the standard reply when ...Bg4 is not a thing.You can definitely consider the 'life hack' approach5...a6with the idea to meet6.Nf3Bg4!and we are getting back into the usual stuff (this works great in online games from my experience), but this could become tricky if White does not rush to develop the knight and we end up playing ...Bf5 anyway.6.b4This is the most likely follow up for White.6...cxd4!It's important not to go6...cxb4because of7.axb4!7.cxd4e68.Nf3Nge7We are simply going for the universal regroupment with ...Nc8-Nb6 and then castling short.9.Bb2Nc810.Nbd2Be711.Be2O-O12.O-ONb6=Black is perfectly safe. Keep in mind that Nb3 can be answered by ...Na4!, while in case White does nothing special, we can continue with ...Rc8-Rc7-Qc8 and then the computer comes up with a sick maneuver going ...a6-Na7-Nb5! putting pressure on the queenside.C)5.Na3This can be an interesting idea for White against the French Defense, preparing to play Nc2 ➼ making sure the d4-square is well protected. In fact, it is something that I used to do myself with very decent results (starting1.e4e62.d4d53.e5c54.c3Nc65.Nf3Qb66.Na3).5...cxd4!6.cxd4Bf5=Because of this move, White's plan simply backfires. They would love to play Nc3 in this position, but the knight is already committed to a3. We can continue with normal play ...e6-Nge7 and White has two plans: A) play with Bd3 where we can trade bishops and go ...Nf5-Be7 followed by ...O-O; B) play with Be2 where we can stick with the universal ...Nc8-Nb6 followed by ...Be7 and ...O-O with good play on the queenside.} 
5. Bg4 {While there are many ways to play against this set-up (a lot of them a transposition to the French Defense), it's important to stay away from the natural5...Bf56.dxc5!Nxe57.Ng3!and White has a small initiaitve.} 
6. f3 {This is the most common move by far.6.h3This  leads to typical positions for the 'Advance Variation'!6...Bxe2Remember that ➼ we always take vs the 'Advance'.7.Bxe2e68.O-Ocxd49.cxd4Nge710.Nc3Nf511.Be3Be7=with standard positions for the 'Advance' where Black has no problems.} 
6. Bf5 {It's important that we provoked this f3-weakening which makes Black's position very playable now. White now has a variety of moves, but none of them are particularly dangerous.} 
7. Ng3 {This is the most popular move online.7.g4This is also quite popular for White in online chess. I recommend we play the same way as against 7.Ng3 for the sake of simplicity.7...Bxb1!8.Rxb1e69.Bg2cxd410.cxd4Bb4+This makes kingisde development a walk in the park.11.Bd2Bxd2+12.Qxd2Nge7∞While there is nothing wrong with ...O-O and playing solidly, we can also choose a more aggressive path by going ...Qb6 followed by O-O-O with ...h5 ideas (taking advantage of the g4-hook).7.dxc5!?This has been the main try in OTB chess.7...Nxe58.Nd48.Ng3Bc8!This is the safest square for the bishop.It's important to watch out for8...Bg6??9.f4!followed by f5 and White wins a piece.9.Bb5+Nc610.O-Og6!This move not only prepares ...Bg7, but also restricts the g3-knight!11.Re1Bg712.Bf4Nf613.Nd2O-O =with a solid position for Black. If White is not careful, we can go for the ...d4 push and grab the initiative!8...Bd7!Defending against Bb5+ ideas.9.f4Nc6=We can continue with ...Nf6 followed by ...g6-Bg7 and ...O-O!} 
7. Bxb1 {Generally this is a questionable decision, but due to White's g3-knight and kingside ideas based on h4-h5 (hunting our light squared bishop) ➼ this trade seems to be pretty smart because it leads to a position that is easy to play.} 
8. Rxb1
8. cxd4
9. cxd4
9. Qb6 {White does not have an easy way to protect the d4-pawn.} 
10. Be3 {This is a very common mistake! Of course, it's better to play10.Ne2e6, but Black has at least equal chances there.} 
10. Nxe5 {This can be easily overlooked! White is in trouble because11.dxe5Qxe3+!is very annoying (see why it was so important to provoke f3 earlier?!).} 
