4. Nc3 {This is quite rare, but the important idea to remember is that we might have to play with the locked bishop.A)4.c4This will most likely get us back into the 4.Nf3 Nc6 5.c4 line.4...cxd45.Nf3Nc6With a direct transposition.B)4.Be3This is rare, but pretty common below 1200 from my experience.4...cxd45.Bxd4Nc66.Bb5The only 'tricky' move since 6.Nf3 Bg4 leads to an easy game for Black because we can continue with the typical development.6...Bd7Breaking the pin and threatening ...Nxd4 with favorable trades for us.7.Bxc6bxc6We always take with the pawn in this structure so that we can push ...c5 later and build up a strong center.8.Nf3e69.O-Oc510.Be3Qb6Creating a pretty unpleasant threat against the b2-pawn.11.b3Ne712.Nbd2Nf5⩱We can continue with ...Be7 followed by ...O-O and Black is very solid.C)4.f4This is 'the most common rare move'. Kind of ironic, I know, but I've seen this get played against my students occasionally.4...cxd4With this move we are destroying White's center while inviting the enemy queen to recapture and expose herself.5.Qxd45.Nf3With this move, White is trying to recapture on d4 with the knight.5...Bg4!All of a sudden White is in a pretty problematic situation very early on in the game!6.Qxd4can hardly be a good idea after6...Bxf3➼ and White's kingside is weakened for the rest of the game.6.Bd3Nc67.O-Oe68.h3Bxf3!Remember to always take vs the 'Advance Variation'!9.Qxf3g6⩱This is a nice little idea because it slows down White's counterplay based on the f5-push. We can finish development with ...Nge7 followed by ...Bg7 with ...O-O!5...Nc6Developing with tempo.6.Bb5a6Forcing White to give up the bishop pair because7.Ba4??b5!wins a piece.7.Bxc6+bxc68.Nf3e69.O-ONh6=We can finish development with ...Be7 followed by ...O-O! Then we are ready to push in the center with ...c5 while the light squared bishop can always activate by playing ...a5-Ba6!D)4.Bd3Quite rare and easy to handle.4...cxd45.Nf3Nc66.O-OBg4=We can continue with normal development while