2. d4
2. d5
3. e5 {This is the starting position of the 'Advance Variation' ➼ the choice of anyone who wants to be at least semi-ambitious when it comes to the opening battle. From my experience this variation is usually the main pain point for most of the people I've worked with, so hey, you are not alone!Before explaining the position, it's important to understand that Black has two main options:•3...Bf5➼ which is the main choice in Grandmaster games. This move will not be covered in the course, but if you are above 2200 FIDE rating, I would seriously consider this option because it will pay off in the long run. The 'problem' with this variation is that it really requires a lot of knowledge, and usually forgetting a move can get you in trouble big time.•3...c5(The Botvinnik-Carls Defense) ➼ which is our main line in this course! From a theoretical perspective, this variation is completely fine, but will sometimes require us to lock the light squared bishop inside the pawn chain by playing ...e6 (with positions that are typical for the French Defense).Understanding when/how to play with the passive light-squared bishop is the real challenge when going for3...c5, but the good news is that if you are playing the Caro-Kann below 2200, literally nobody will have a proper understanding of these positions ➼ often going for harmless lines that are very easy to play for Black with little to no theoretical knowledge about the opening.What I really love about this specific line is that most of the times you can get away with simply understanding the pawn structure & remembering where each piece should be placed.} 
3. c5 {After this move the wide player pool will react the following way:  •4.c3(50%)  •4.dxc5(20%)  •4.Nf3(20%)   • and the rest are super rare.From a theoretical perspective, the most dangerous move is known to be4.dxc5, ➼ referred to by many as the only way to play for an advantage. Personally I consider this move to be the biggest 'memory test' for Black, as the lines should be completely harmless.Recently, top level Grandmasters have even started to switch on to the 'let's get a fresh position' approach by going4.Nf3, which is an indication that4.dxc5is no longer considered to be problematic for Black.} 
4. Nf3 {This move used to be pretty rare at the top level, but nowadays this is becoming one of the most popular replies for White against the 'Botvinnik-Carls' variation. The main reason for this phenomenon is that Black started holding his ground pretty well against the 'well established' move (4.dxc5).White players are happy to go for more minimalistic approach with4.Nf3, allowing4...cxd45.Nxd4Nc66.Nxc6bxc67.Bd3e6and White has a slightly more pleasant position to play because of their active bishop.This is the current 'meta' at the top level, and even though I feel like Black is perfectly fine there with proper play, I think it's clever to play the move4...Nc6instead ➼ fully taking advantage of the way our repertoire is structured. This of course, makes sense because our plan is to meet4.dxc5with4...Nc6(and not4...e6).In case you still want to go for4.dxc5e6(if not, just skip this part to avoid confusion), it will be difficult to follow my repertoire because White has the option of meeting4.Nf3Nc6with5.dxc5!which would transpose to the4.dxc5Nc6lines (meaning that you will have to learn both as a4.dxc5e6player).I hope that is not very confusing and you are still with me! One last trick to mention though: in case you really want to stick with4.dxc5e6, you can try to meet4.Nf3by going for the rare4...Bg4(I will just leave this out there).} 
4. Nc6 {The most flexible move. Please keep in mind that5.dxc5Bg4simply transposes to the 4.dxc5 lines!} 
5. c4 {This move is super rare, but really dangerous if you don't know how to handle it properly.} 
5. cxd4
6. Nxd4 {6.cxd5is a rare continuation, leading to some pretty double-edged positions. It's important to be aware of it, but I don't expect your opponents to play this properly (generally speaking).6...Qxd57.Nc3Qa5!This is the simplest. 7...Qd8 could lead to some pretty strange lines!8.Nxd4Qxe5+9.Be3Bd7This is important because White is about to throw in Bb5-Qf3 ideas to put pressure on the c6-knight.10.Bb5Nf611.Nxc6bxc612.Qf3Qc713.O-O-ONd5!Exploiting the little dance between the c1-king and the c7-queen.14.Bc4e6=We are ready to play ...Be7 and ...O-O, and if White plays15.Bd4the move15...Qf4+seems pretty safe.} 
6. e6 {I know it hurts to lock in the light squared bishop, but we need to adapt to White's play. Chess is a very reactive game, compare it to tennis if you will. Our shots are always dependent on what our opponent is doing. Like in tennis, first you need to see where the enemy shot is about to land and then you need to figure out a way to return it in a convenient way. You can't play tennis blindfolded, same as you can't play chess ignoring your opponent's moves!White's c4 is simply putting way too much pressure over the center, and the best way to handle it is to make a small concession and play the defensive move 6...e6! The good news is that White is also overextending a bit with this plan, making it easier for us to counter-attack.} 
7. Nc3 {This is the main move for OTB chess, and the only serious test.} 
7. Bc5 {Developing with tempo. We should stay away from the greedy7...Nxe5?because of8.cxd5exd59.Bb5+!with a winning position for White.} 
8. Nxc6 {This is White's only dangerous try. In case of8.Nb3, the reply8...Bb4gives Black a simple game with ...Nge7 and ...O-O next.} 
8. bxc6
9. Qg4 {9.cxd5cxd510.b4!?White's only serious continuation if they play 9.cxd5.10...Be711.a3This has to be played because11.Bd3Qc7!is good for Black.11...a5!?12.bxa5Nh613.Bxh6gxh614.Bb5+Bd715.O-OQxa516.Bxd7+Kxd7=The position seems pretty messy, but Black's king is quite safe in the middle.} 
9. Ne7 {The only reasonable way of dealing with White's threat. Black is getting a good position in the following complicated line.} 
10. Qxg7 {The following moves are pretty forcing.10.Bd3This was tried by Carlsen in a blitz game, but White couldn't get an edge even there.10...O-O11.O-ONg6White is struggling to keep the e5-pawn well protected.12.Na4Nxe513.Bxh7+Kxh714.Qh5+Kg815.Nxc5Nxc416.b3Nd617.Bb2f6=1-0 Carlsen,M (2837)-Moskalenko,A (2522) Titled Tuesday intern op 17th April Chess.com INT blitz 2017 (6). White of course has some compensation, but Black is very solid.} 
10. Ng6
11. Be2
11. Bf8
12. Qf6
12. Be7
13. Qf3
13. d4
14. Ne4
14. Qa5+
15. Bd2
15. Qxe5 {You could definitely go a bit deeper with analysing this position, but I think for such a rare line we have more than enough. In any case, the game could go basically into two main directions:A)16.O-O-Of517.Ng5Rb818.Bd3Qc519.Rhe1Qa3!20.bxa3Bxa3+21.Kc2Rb2+with the funniest perpetual of all time;B)16.O-ORb817.Rae1Rxb218.Bd3Qg719.Qh5f520.Bh6Qf721.Ng5Bxg522.Qxg5Rg8with a complex position, but Black should be at least not worse.} 
