4. Nc6 {The most flexible move. Please keep in mind that5.dxc5Bg4simply transposes to the 4.dxc5 lines!} 
5. Bb5
5. Bg4
6. Bxc6+ {The only move with independent value. The computer can be pretty annoying with this concept, but generally people who go for this will play much worse (it's simply not logical to give up the bishop pair like that, and it's generally played by the weaker players).} 
6. bxc6
7. dxc5 {This is the only sensible move.A common mistake for lower rated players is7.h3?Bxf3!8.Qxf3cxd4and Black simply has an extra pawn!} 
7. e6
8. b4 {This is by far the most common move for White here. Against the surprisingly popular8.h3, our reply8...Bxf3!9.Qxf3Bxc5is simply good for Black.8.Be3The computer likes this idea, but we have a clever/typical way of dealing with this situation specifically because White has included Bxc6.8...Bxf39.Qxf3Qb8!This idea should always be in the back of your mind when the b-file has been opened.10.Bd4Nh611.O-ONf512.Qd3Qb4∞Winning back the pawn with a solid position.} 
8. Qb8 {Attacking both b4 and e5! This move is critical when White throws in Bxc6 and we recapture with the pawn.} 
9. Qd4 {The only move to keep the extra pawn since9.c3Bxf3!10.Qxf3a5!?is already better for us.} 
9. Bxf3 {Whenever we can damage White's pawn structure like this, it is usually the best move!} 
10. gxf3
10. Ne7 {The knight is about to land on f5 followed by the ...a5-break on the queenside. White has a hard time keeping everything together.} 
