1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. e5
3. c5
4. dxc5 {This is the most critical test for our whole repertoire, so make sure to study this chapter religiously (in case you are above 1800). If that information may sound surprising, I see you already skipped the Introduction to the course and I just wanted to let you know that I feel absolutely betrayed! Anyway, let's move on...} 
4. Nc6 {This is our trademark move, the bread and butter of the Advance Variation. The goal is to get our light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain as often as we can, even at the risk of 'losing' a pawn in some variations. It is actually a well thought-out sacrifice, trust me! Repeat that mantra every time you blunder a pawn, and your results will improve by 50% at least.} 
5. Nf3 {5.Bb5The sad story about this move is that it forces us to play with a locked bishop since there is no convenient way of developing in a different fashion.5...e6Finally we must play with the locked bishop, what a sad story I know...If you call winning all of your games and becoming a chess god sad, this is incredibly sad! Jokes aside, Black should be completely fine in these variations. I picked a pretty instructive variation for you!6.Be3Nge77.c3Bd7Unpinning and threatening to win the e5-pawn.8.Bxc6Bxc6This move is important because the knight will be activated using the f5-square.9.Nf3Nf510.Bd4Nxd411.cxd4This is a common mistake for White. I mean, at the end of the day it looks very natural to 'improve' your pawn structure, but this simply gives Black great counterplay after using a standard idea for the variation.11...b6!You should also clench your fist after making this move because the situation is about to get wild. White is in a world of trouble without even realizing it... Yet!12.cxb6Qxb6⇆Threatening to win the b2-pawn while also preparing the cunning ...Bb5 move which will keep White's king in the center for an eternity - for so long that they may start putting the pieces back on their initial squares because of how bad White's position can get if you follow the analysis from the trainable.5.f4This is White's best bet, objectively speaking. From my experience there are two possible scenarios while facing the line: A) your opponent is lower rated and he just knows the first 5 moves and then has a complete meltdown; B) your opponent is higher rated and you are going to lose regardless.5...Nh6!It's all about getting that ...Bg4 move baby! At this point White has a number of different tries.6.Nf3This is by far the most common reply.6.c3Easy to overlook, this line is full of venom!6...Bg47.Qb3The real point of starting with c3!For some reason I've got a disturbingly high number of stronger players that went7.Be2against me, which gives Black a perfectly fine position after7...e6!7...Qc7!8.h38...Bd7∞Leading to interesting complications, so make sure to check out the trainable.6...Bg47.Bd3This is White's best attempt according to the computer.7...Qa5+8.c3Qxc5∞With a complicated positions where I think Black has very interesting prospects against any player. For online chess, I think this is pure gold because they will never figure out what to do in time, and even for OTB this can be pretty reliable. Imagine that against the most natural move 9.Qe2  (preparing Be3 followed by O-O) Black has the stunning 9...Nd4!! which leads to fire on the board! So make sure to check out the trainables.} 
5. Bg4
6. c3 {This used to be one of the main ways for White to play for an advantage.6.Bb5e67.b4Nge78.c3g6=Simply preparing to finish development with ...Bg7 followed by ...O-O and then we are going to put pressure on the queenside with ...a5!} 
6. e6 {This is my main move because it's super natural and quite playable. I have to say White could grab a very tiny edge against it, so in case you are someone higher rated I would recommend to have a look at the alternative with 6...a6 which is also covered in the course.} 
7. Be3 {7.b4Bxf38.Qxf3Nxe5=With a fine position for Black. This time 9.Bb5+ Nc6 10.c4 a5! gives Black good counterplay because the b4-pawn is vulnerable. For more details make sure to check out the trainable!} 
7. Bxf3
8. Qxf3
8. Nge7 {This move is quite important!8...Nxe5?!This is very tempting, but if White is precise, Black can get in trouble.9.Bb5+Nc610.c4↑White is getting a pretty annoying initiative.} 
9. Bb5
9. a6
10. Ba4
10. Qa5 {Putting pressure on White's center. Now they have a choice, so for more details make sure to check out the trainables!} 
