7. bxc6
8. Be3 {Another move that is simply trying to hang on the c5-pawn, but we can refute it in a fashion similar to8.b4.} 
8. Bxf3
9. Qxf3
9. Qb8 {This is the key move to really print in your mind because it makes it very difficult for White to protect both pawns.} 
10. Bd4
10. Ne7 {The following will be a pretty messy computer-ish line (for both colours), but it is truly best play for both sides.A quick sidenote: It's important to stay away from the tempting10...Bxc5because White gets a winning position (surprisingly) after11.Bxc5Qxb212.O-OQxa113.Qg3!and Black is dead lost.} 
11. Qb3
11. Nf5
12. c3
12. f6
13. exf6
13. gxf6 {This was the surprising move to me!} 
14. Bxf6
14. Rg8 {We will regain one of the pawns by force, after which Black keeps good compensation in the center and on the kingside.} 
