9. g6 {Sticking with the simple plan.} 
10. h3
10. Bxf3 {Always take on f3 against the 'Advance Variation'!(Yes, I won't stop barking at you.)} 
11. Nxf3
11. Bg7
12. O-O
12. O-O {Now White is in a pretty difficult spot, having to protect both b4 and e5.} 
13. Qe1 {The only move to keep both pawns protected.} 
13. Qc7
14. Bf4
14. axb4
15. cxb4
15. Ra3 {This is the key idea to keep full compensation. Allow White to push a4 and you are doomed to failure. After this move, Black's position becomes really fun to play since White does not have an easy way of getting rid of our rook. Keep in mind that most of his pieces need to cover the e5-pawn, making it very tricky for him to multi-task.} 
