[Round "?"]
[White "2) Advance With 4.dxc5"]
[Black "4.dxc5 Nc6 5.Nf3 Bg4 6.Bb5 e6 with 7.b4 & 8.O-O"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. e5 {This is the starting position of the 'Advance Variation' ➼ the choice of anyone who wants to be at least semi-ambitious when it comes to the opening battle. From my experience this variation is usually the main pain point for most of the people I've worked with, so hey, you are not alone!Before explaining the position, it's important to understand that Black has two main options:•3...Bf5➼ which is the main choice in Grandmaster games. This move will not be covered in the course, but if you are above 2200 FIDE rating, I would seriously consider this option because it will pay off in the long run. The 'problem' with this variation is that it really requires a lot of knowledge, and usually forgetting a move can get you in trouble big time.•3...c5(The Botvinnik-Carls Defense) ➼ which is our main line in this course! From a theoretical perspective, this variation is completely fine, but will sometimes require us to lock the light squared bishop inside the pawn chain by playing ...e6 (with positions that are typical for the French Defense).Understanding when/how to play with the passive light-squared bishop is the real challenge when going for3...c5, but the good news is that if you are playing the Caro-Kann below 2200, literally nobody will have a proper understanding of these positions ➼ often going for harmless lines that are very easy to play for Black with little to no theoretical knowledge about the opening.What I really love about this specific line is that most of the times you can get away with simply understanding the pawn structure & remembering where each piece should be placed.} 
3. c5 {After this move the wide player pool will react the following way:  •4.c3(50%)  •4.dxc5(20%)  •4.Nf3(20%)   • and the rest are super rare.From a theoretical perspective, the most dangerous move is known to be4.dxc5, ➼ referred to by many as the only way to play for an advantage. Personally I consider this move to be the biggest 'memory test' for Black, as the lines should be completely harmless.Recently, top level Grandmasters have even started to switch on to the 'let's get a fresh position' approach by going4.Nf3, which is an indication that4.dxc5is no longer considered to be problematic for Black.} 
4. dxc5 {This is the main move at master level, but very rare below 2200. Known as the only real test of Black's 3...c5, this capture leads to fascinating positions.} 
4. Nc6 {This may come as a surprise to a lot of the 'experienced' Caro players. While4...e6is known to be the best move at the top level nowadays and has proven to be an equalizer according to the computer, I think the resulting positions are quite difficult to understand/remember (especially for players below 2000). With my approach, the goal is to play with an active light-squared bishop as often as we can (although there will be some situations where there is nothing better than locking in the bishop).From a theoretical perspective, after4...Nc6the move5.f4is known to be the most serious test for Black, but I came up with a new approach that makes it very difficult for White to play. With best moves for both sides they will still be able to get approximately a +0.4 advantage according to the computer, but I did my best to explain the upcoming positions.Overall I think this variation will really boost your chess improvement, because it teaches a lot of fundamental themes such as:   • how to play typical endgames;   • how to sacrifice a pawn for long term compensation;   • how to undermine White's queenside;   • how to get the initiative when White is careless;   • how to remember the opening by ideas (not move by move).} 
5. Nf3 {This is the most common move for White, and you are going to face it about 40% of the time.} 
5. Bg4 {If possible, we love to get the light squared bishop outside the pawn chain before playing ...e6(trying to recapture the pawn with ...Bxc5)and then finish development with ...Nge7 + short castle. Now White has a pretty wide choice, but around 50% of the time they will develop their light-squared bishop!} 
6. Bb5 {Going Bb5 is generally not very critical in most Caro-Kann positions, but in this particular example, the move is very sensible because it makes it difficult for us to regain the pawn.} 
6. e6 {This is the simplest move!At first I got really excited after entering the rabbit hole arising after6...Qa5+which leads to some fascinating variations really! For example,7.Nc3e68.Be3Nge79.a3O-O-O!and I think Black should be fine objectively speaking. The line is pretty forcing and will usually continue10.b4Bxf3!11.gxf3Qc712.Bxc6Nxc613.Bf4a6(stopping Nb5, and Black is doing just fine), but then I asked myself 'Who is really going to remember this crazy madness, move by move?'.Now if you have some kind of lizard galaxy brain, definitely give this one a try, but I would recommend the simpler choice overall (especially because it's way more decent that expected!).} 
7. b4 {This move together with7.Be3are White's most common replies, and for a good reason. At the end of the day, White is simply trying to hang on to their extra pawn, and there's nothing wrong with that!The good news is that against both, we can usually play ...Nge7 followed by ...g6-Bg7 with a solid position for Black. We will castle short and always answer h3 with ...Bxf3 followed by ...a5/b6 ideas to create counterplay on the queenside (pretty simple if you ask me!).} 
7. Nge7 {After this move White has a few alternatives, but our general strategy won't change much.} 
8. O-O
8. a5
9. c3
9. g6 {For the sake of simplicity we are going to stick with this move, but keep in mind that in this specific position9...Ng6could also be a very decent alternative.} 
10. Bg5 {This is White's most ambitious try.} 
10. Bxf3
11. Qxf3
11. Bg7
12. Bf6
12. Bxf6 {This may look pretty scary, but in reality we are luring White's queen onto a pretty useless square.} 
13. Qxf6 {13.exf6Against this we are simply going to collect the f6-pawn.13...Nf5Threatening14.--Qxf6because on15.g4there is15...Qg5!because the pawn is pinned and the knight escapes.14.g4This may seem to be a bit annoying, but Black has a great resource to keep in mind.14...Nh4!15.Qf4The only move to keep the f6-pawn protected.15...g5∓. Now16.Qxg5??Nf3+wins the house for Black, and other moves just allow ...Qxf6 with a great position for Black.} 
13. O-O {We are most likely going to win back the pawn because White is struggling to keep the queenside together.} 
