6. a3 {White is simply preparing to push b4. The problem with this plan however, is that Black is able to successfully undermine White's queenside.A)6.Bf4With this move, White is simply protecting the e5-pawn, but fails to save its younger brother, the c5-pawn.6...e67.h3Bxf38.Qxf3Bxc5⩱We can continue with ...Nge7 followed by ...O-O and then ...Ng6 will make it very uncomfortable for White to defend the e5-pawn.B)6.h3This move will get played around 1/10 games, but it clearly does not pose any problems to Black.6...Bxf3In the 'Advance Variation' we always take in reply to h3!7.Qxf3e6Threatening to regain the pawn with ...Bxc5 and getting ready to complete development.8.Be3Nge7!This is even more precise than8...Nxe5because then9.Bb5+Nc610.c4gives White a small initiative.9.Bb5Qa5+!Forcing Nc3, will make White vulnerable to ...d4 ideas (which could win the game for us because of the fork).10.Nc3a611.Bxc6+11.Ba4?This move simply gets White in trouble!11...O-O-O∓0-1 Carlsson,P (2476)-Fridman,D (2654) Gibraltar Masters 8th Caleta 2010 (9). With ...d4 being a huge threat, White most likely has to give up the piece, but Black should definitely be able to keep a better position.11...Nxc6=We are ready to regain the pawn on the very next move with a solid position for Black.C)6.Be3This move is super rare, but it could be tricky to deal with.6...d4!This is the key idea to fully equalise. We are going to follow it up with ...e6 followed by ...Bxc5!7.Bf4e68.Nbd2Bxc59.h3Bxf310.Qxf3Nge711.Bd3Bb4!This is important because we are making sure that White is not in time to play Ne4.12.O-OBxd213.Bxd2Ng6=We are most likely going to pick up the e5-pawn next, but White should be able to keep decent compensation with the bishop pair.} 
6. e6
7. b4
7. a5
8. c3 {This is the lesser evil because8.b5Nxe5!is very promising for Black.} 
8. Bxf3
9. Qxf3
9. Qc7 {This is even stronger than simply recapturing the pawn, because ...Qxe5+ is now a huge threat.} 
10. Bf4
