6. Be3 {This is by far the main line for White, because it's the only reasonable move that keeps the extra pawn.6.Nf3This is a common move for the lower rated players that are accidentaly playing 4.dxc5 and then they just don't know what to do.6...Bxc57.O-ONge7Generally speaking Black is getting a great position after ...O-O followed by ...Ng6 and the ...f6-break.8.Bg5This is not great, but I think it really makes sense to have it here because the lower-rated players will always go for the 'Taekwandoo bishops'.8...h69.Bh4a6Questioning both bishops is the way to go now that we almost finished development.10.Bxc6+bxc611.Nbd2g5!Not the only way to proceed, but the most annoying one.12.Bg3Nf5∓White is about to get steamrolled by ...h5-h4! That is simply deadly because any h3 move will drop the bishop after ...Nxg3 as the f-pawn is pinned by the c5-bishop!} 
6. Nge7
7. Nf3 {This is quite popular in online chess, but it's a pretty large inaccuracy.} 
7. Nf5
8. Bd4 {Common for online chess.8.b4Bd7!While 8...Nxe3 is playable, our move is simply better.9.Bxc6Bxc610.Bd4a5!The queenside undermining is simply too strong.11.c3axb412.cxb4b6!13.O-Obxc514.bxc5Be715.Nbd2O-O⩱We can easily regain the pawn, while Black's position is ultra solid. We can continue with moves such as ...Ra4-Qa8 and the light-squared bishop can be activated with ...Bb5!} 
8. Nfxd4
9. Qxd4
9. Qa5+ {This simply wins back the pawn by force.} 
10. Nc3
