8. c3
8. Qxc5 {Since this is a new position it is pretty difficult to predict what our opponent will play, but I will add all the important moves you need to be aware of ➼ to safely drive in this lane at any level.} 
9. h3 {This is White's most common move out of the few games that I was able to find in the Lichess online database. It looks very natural and strong because it forces us to give up the bishop pair, and after Qxf3 White seems to easily finish development with Be3 followed by O-O with a crushing position. The good news is that Black has a concrete little idea that will throw off a lot of the White players!*9.Nbd2I don't really expect you face this often, but I wanted to mention that we can simply go for ...Qe3+!The main thing to avoid is9...e610.Nb3!and White is much better.9...Qe3+!10.Be2e611.Nb3Qb612.Nfd4This is White's only reasonable move.12...Bxe213.Qxe2Nxd414.Nxd4Bc515.Be3Rc816.O-ONf5!Allowing the doubled pawns is not something standard, but it is a very efficient way of solving the issue of the h6-knight being caught a little bit offside.17.Nxf5exf518.Bxc5Rxc5=We are mainly playing for a draw, but only one weakness on d5 should be defendable without much trouble.} 
9. Bxf3 {Always meet h3 with takes in the 'Advance Variation'!} 
10. Qxf3
10. Nb4 {The double exclam mark is of course, a bit exagerated, but if you are failing to remember this move I think Black's position is doomed. Make sure to really use the MoveTrainer on this line (in case you are around 2200 Fide-2500 online) because it can easily make the difference from losing to winning.} 
11. Nd2 {This is the more human move, simply making sure that the c1-bishop is protected and threatening to take the b4-knight.} 
11. Nxd3+
12. Qxd3
12. e6
13. g4 {This is important because if White allows ...Nf5, the tables could easily turn since Black becomes very active.} 
13. Ng8 {We have to play this sad move in order to reinforce the knight.} 
14. Nb3
14. Qc7
15. Be3
15. Ne7
16. O-O-O
16. Nc6 {The knight is now on a reasonable square. It took a bit of time, but we finally did it!} 
17. Kb1
17. O-O-O {This has to be played because castling kingside will be really asking for trouble or as we say in Romania, 'you'd be entering wolf's mouth' lol.} 
18. Nd4
18. Be7
19. Rhe1
19. h5 {White definitely has a slightly more pleasant game due to the extra space, but Black's position is very solid with no weaknesses.} 
