5. Nh6 {This is the key move to start with. The most popular move (5...e6) gives White a massive win rate close to 70% in OTB chess ➼ so it's definitely something that we need to avoid!} 
6. Be3 {This move is quite rare, but it can be super tricky to deal with if unprepared. Our reflex is to go for6...Bg4, but once White plays7.Qd2!our move is not really making a lot of sense since White can follow up with h3, pushing back our bishop.} 
6. g5 {This is the key move to get great counterplay. The alternatives are just worse, but once you remember 6...g5, the rest is pretty straightforward and White needs to be careful.} 
7. fxg5 {7.Nf3Nf5!Capturing the important dark squared bishop or winning the f4-pawn.8.Bf2gxf4=With at least an equal game because we managed to destroy White's center.} 
7. Ng4 {This move is critical to equalize. Here is why it is so important to play6...g5!directly and not6...Bg47.Qd2g5because our bishop would be in the way.} 
8. Bf4 {8.Bd4Ngxe5Threatening ...Nxd4 followed by ...Bg7!9.Bxe5Nxe510.Nf3Bg711.Nxe5Bxe512.Nc3Rg8=With full equality.} 
8. Ngxe5
9. Nc3
9. Ng6
10. Bg3
10. Bg7
11. Nxd5
11. O-O
12. c3 {This is White's best try because12.Nc7Bxb2!gives Black enough counterplay.} 
12. Qa5
13. b4
13. Qa3 {After this key move Black gets very decent chances, since White is more or less forced to go for14.Qc1Nxb4!which leads to a balanced endgame.} 
