[White "3) Exchange Variation"]
[Black "Exchange Variation: Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4 {This is the traditional way of playing for White. In case you are below 1500 you will get move orders such as2.Nc3d53.exd5or2.Nf3d53.exd5a lot, so don't panic because they will transpose into our normal lines.This is the nice thing about the Caro-Kann because we don't have to learn dozens of lines to get a playable position. As long as you understand the big ideas from the main lines, you can easily crush weird deviations without any prior knowldege, simply because you understand the typical pawn structures.} 
2. d5
3. exd5
3. cxd5
4. Bd3 {This is known to be the most ambitious way to play this variation as White. From my experience, hardly anyone plays it below 2000, and you will normally just face inferior lines such as 4.Nf3 or 4.Nc3!4.Nf3This can very well transpose to 4.Nc3 lines, but there is also a trickier idea for White.4...Nc65.Ne5Threatening to play Bb5, hoping to win the bishop pair. This is something that Magnus Carlsen used to do quite a lot in rapid time controls.5...a6=After this nice move, most of White's plans have been ruined. For more details check out the trainables.4.Nc3Random moves like this one can always be answered by the simple ...Nc6-Nf6-Bg4-e6-Be7 followed by ...O-O with ...Rc8 and Black is attacking on the queenside thanks to the minority attack (...a6-b5-Na5-Nc4).} 
4. Nf6 {Our move order is very important against 4.Bd3 because we need to be in time with this very concrete idea of playing ...Bg4 so that we can meet Qb3 with ...Qc7!} 
5. c3 {This is the most common move for White because that's the general strategy to meet ...Bg4 ideas with Qb3 and they were pretty happy with it in the past... Until Black discovered the stunning 6. ..Qc7 idea!5.h3This is one of the main tries nowadays for White, because Black has proven to be very solid after 5.c3 Bg4 thanks to many games by Alireza Firouzja and Vincent Keymer.5...Nc66.c3g6!?Preparing to play ...Bf5 and swap the bishops. We must stay away from 6...e6 where Black can easily get a passive position.7.Nf3This is by far the most natural move for White.7.Qc2This move may raise an eyebrow because Black can no longer get the bishop trade.7...e5=This move works really well because we are getting a lot of activity in exchange for the IQP. Make sure to check out the trainable for more info!7...Bf5Avoiding the bad bishop at all costs! (not really) We are just getting a very interesting pawn structure in case White takes.8.Bxf5You are going to see this move about half of your games whenever a similar position appears on the board. I consider it to be a practical mistake when White trades on f5 with Black's bishop still flexible on f8. In case we have already committed to ...Bg7, the trade makes a lot more sense and White is generally slightly better in that structure. With the bishop still on f8, this makes a huge difference because we are going to play with ...e6-Bd6 while making use of the g-file with ...Rg8 followed by ...O-O-O in a lot of variations.8.O-OThis is White's best move objectively speaking, and the mainline among stronger players. In the course I also mention all the other rare alternatives such as 8.Be2, 8.Bb5 and 8.Ne5.8...Bxd39.Qxd3Qc7=Stopping White from playing Bf4 always makes them feel like a kid who just dropped his cone of icecream on the floor during a sunny day.8...gxf59.O-ORg8∞This move not only aims the cannon at White's king, but also prepares to meet10.Bg5with the very annoying10...Ne4!} 
5. Bg4 {Move order really matters in this specific line, so make sure to take advantage of the move trainer technology by Chessable!} 
6. Qb3
6. Qc7 {Protecting the b7-pawn while also stopping White's main idea of playing Bf4, which would transpose to London System type of positions.} 
7. h3 {This is White's only try to 'refute' our idea.7.Ne2This is the most popular move for White, threatening to develop by gaining tempo with Bf4.7...Bxe2!It turns out that Black is really comfortable despite giving up the bishop pair this early (which back in the days was White's dream scenario).8.Bxe2e6=We are going to finish development with ...Bd6-Nc6-h6, short castle, followed by the minority attack with ...Rab8-b5. Black has good prospects on the queenside.} 
7. Bh5
8. g4 {With this move White is winning a pawn, but we shall not panic. Rule number one: whenever you blunder, ALWAYS act like it was a well planned sacrifice! It may work if your opponent drops his brain on the floor.8.Ne2This move is really tricky if you don't pay attention to the details. I typically expect the White players to be around 2200 at least to know this, but the idea is that the standard 8...Bxe2 now allows 9.Bf4! this time and White is better.8...Nc69.Bf4This is honestly, not the end of the world.9...Qd7=We can finish development by playing ...e6-Bd6 with a balanced position.} 
8. Bg6
9. Bxg6
9. hxg6
10. g5
10. Nfd7
11. Qxd5
11. e5 {We are going to play ...Nc6 followed by long castle with full compensation for the pawn. I think these positions are very risky to play for White!} 
