6. e6
7. h3
7. Bxf3 {We always meet h3 with ...Bxf3 in the 'Exchange Variation' when White has played Bb5, because7...Bh5allows8.g4Bg69.Ne5which can be very dangerous.} 
8. Qxf3
8. Nf6
9. Bg5
9. Be7 {Making sure that Bxf6 is never a problem.} 
10. O-O {This is a bit more common than castling long, but you'd be surprised how many people go10.O-O-Oas well!} 
10. O-O {After this move, we have unpinned the c6-knight, so ...Nxd4 becomes a huge threat which a lot of lower rated players tend to forget about!If you want to be ultra precise, you can also throw in10...Rc8so you can take back with THE ROOK.} 
11. Rad1
11. Rc8
12. Rfe1
12. a6 {Now we are ready to meet13.Bxc6with13...Rxc6!followed by ...b5 with annoying pressure on the queenside.} 
13. Bf1
13. b5 {The following moves by White won't make a whole lot of sense, but the main point is to understand what the optimal set-up for Black's pieces is.13...Qb6This is a common mistake generally because Black is blocking their main fundamental plan 'The Minority Attack'. Generally the queen is only well placed on this square if it's behind the pawns.} 
14. a3
14. Qb6
15. Be3
15. Na5 {This is the key manuever to remember against the Nc3 lines. Too many players rush with15...b4which leads to messy positions.} 
16. Bf4
16. Nc4
17. Bxc4
17. Rxc4 {While17...bxc4is also reasonable, this is my favorite way to recapture.} 
18. Be5
18. Rfc8 {This is the ideal set-up for our pieces. Next up we are ready to push ...a5 followed by ...b4 (always meeting axb4 by recapturing with the pawn) so that after White moves the knight, the c2-pawn is ready to be taken. After that we just try to exchange all the pieces and win the king and pawn endgame! It's really not that complicated, you've got this! :D} 
