[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Exchange Variation"]
[Black "4.Nf3 Nc6 5.Nc3 & 10.O-O-O with 11.Rhe1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. exd5 {This is the traditional way of reaching the Exchange Variation. The important thing to know about this is that by learning the mainlines you will automatically have a very solid understanding which will also apply against the sidelines.For example, in lower rated games it is very common that White will start with move orders such as1.e4c62.Nf3d53.exd5or1.e4c62.Nc3d53.exd5or even1.e4c62.Bc4d53.exd5, which all can be placed into the same bucket of the 'Exchange Variation'. What I love about the Caro-Kann the most is that we can easily predict our opponent's moves, making it super easy to adapt.} 
3. cxd5
4. Nf3 {This could be dangerous if White combines it with Ne5 on the very next move. However, most players below 2000 online rating will not be aware of that plan and generally just get an inferior version of the 'Exchange Variation'.} 
4. Nc6 {Since we are no longer in a rush with the concrete ...Nf6-Bg4 as we are against 4.Bd3, we can start with 4...Nc6 because it already takes the e5-square under control.} 
5. Nc3 {This poor move is incredibly common for lower rated players below 1500 online. The knight simply does not fit well on the c3-square in this 'Carlsbad structure'. It is like a penguin trying to climb a tree ➼ it's out of its element and struggling to find its footing in a place where it just doesn't belong.} 
5. Bg4 {Pinning the knight and preparing to play ...e6 followed by ...Bd6!} 
6. Bb5 {This is super common below 1500.} 
6. e6
7. h3
7. Bxf3 {We always meet h3 with ...Bxf3 in the 'Exchange Variation' when White has played Bb5, because7...Bh5allows8.g4Bg69.Ne5which can be very dangerous.} 
8. Qxf3
8. Nf6
9. Bg5
9. Be7 {Making sure that Bxf6 is never a problem.} 
10. O-O-O {I was able to find a ton of games with this move in online chess, which is quite mind blowing! Black is simply much better in this structure because we can make use of the semi-open c-file to attack White. We basically have a highway towards the enemy king!In opposite castling games it is very important to get your own initiative going. Generally it's just a race, so the player who gets there first should win. A typical mistake would be to panic and start making defensive moves on the kingside while neglecting our own counter-attacking potential.} 
10. Rc8 {Being able to take back with the rook on c6 is always nice. You just want to make sure that White has no way to exploit the king in the middle, and then we are more than fine!} 
11. Rhe1
11. O-O {11...a6?I am just adding this move here to highlight what we need to watch out for!12.Bxc6+Rxc613.Bxf6Bxf6?14.Nxd5±This is the only motif that we need to watch out for in this structure when considering to throw in ...Rc8 before castling.} 
12. g4
12. Qa5 {The queen is super powerful on this square. This move introduces ideas to sacrifice the exchange on c3 followed by ...Qxa2. We will see an example in the clickable attached to White's next move.} 
13. Kb1 {13.h4Nb414.a3Rxc3!This works great because15.bxc3Na2+!is crushing.15.axb4Bxb4!16.bxc3Bxc3-+Most likely winning White's queen because of the mating net.13.Bxc6Rxc614.Bd2Rfc815.Kb1Ra6!This rook lift is devastating because Black has a simple threat of playing ...Bb4-Bxc3 and White loses control over the a2-square.Please keep in mind that moves such as16.a3allow16...Bxa3!and Black is completely taking over.16.g5Ne4-+We are about to eliminate the c3-knight which will leave White's king completely naked in front of a large crowd.} 
13. Nb4 {Creating threats such as ...Ne4 or ...Rxc3-Qxa2!} 
14. a3
14. Nxc2 {This is a typical trick that happens very often from my experience doing the rating climbs on YouTube.} 
15. Kxc2
15. Qxb5 {Taking advantage of the pin. Black has an extra pawn while our attack is only beginning.} 
