1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. exd5 {This is the traditional way of reaching the Exchange Variation. The important thing to know about this is that by learning the mainlines you will automatically have a very solid understanding which will also apply against the sidelines.For example, in lower rated games it is very common that White will start with move orders such as1.e4c62.Nf3d53.exd5or1.e4c62.Nc3d53.exd5or even1.e4c62.Bc4d53.exd5, which all can be placed into the same bucket of the 'Exchange Variation'. What I love about the Caro-Kann the most is that we can easily predict our opponent's moves, making it super easy to adapt.} 
3. cxd5
4. Nf3 {This could be dangerous if White combines it with Ne5 on the very next move. However, most players below 2000 online rating will not be aware of that plan and generally just get an inferior version of the 'Exchange Variation'.} 
4. Nc6 {Since we are no longer in a rush with the concrete ...Nf6-Bg4 as we do against 4.Bd3, we can start with 4...Nc6 because it already takes the e5-square under control.} 
5. Bb5 {This line could have been dangerous if White was in time with Ne5, but we can answer ...Bg4 here.5.Be2This set-up is also harmless for us, and we can just play the natural moves:5...Bg4!Preparing to play ...e6 without locking in the light-squared bishop.6.O-Oe6Preparing to play ...Bd6!7.c3Bd68.h38...Bh5!Keeping the tension! We are not intending to give White the bishop pair for free!9.Re1Qc7Preparing to play ...Nge7 next.10.Nbd2Nge7With the idea to castle short.11.Nf1O-O⩱We can push in the center with ...f6 and ...e5 with a very nice position for Black.} 
5. Bg4 {Pinning the knight and preparing to play ...e6 next. This is the simplest!In case you want to be ultra precise, you can consider going5...Qa5+6.Nc3and only then6...Bg4because the c3-knight is far from ideally placed.} 
6. O-O
6. e6
7. h3
7. Bxf3 {The safest. With the light-squared bishop on b5, this move is generally always good, but if it was on d3 or e2, we never give up the bishop for free. With White's bishop being on b5, we can afford to give up the bishop pair, because we have good pressure on the d4-pawn.} 
8. Qxf3
8. Nf6
9. Bg5 {People who play 5.Bb5 are very likely to do the same with the other bishop.} 
9. Be7
10. c3 {This is the only way to deviate, because10.Nc3transposes to the lines starting with 5.Nc3.} 
10. Qb6 {This move nicely exploits White's lack in development, forcing them to give up the bishop pair.} 
11. Bxc6+
11. bxc6 {This is important so we can break with ...c5!} 
12. b3 {The lesser evil because12.b4a5!gives Black a great initiative on the queenside.} 
12. O-O
13. Nd2
13. c5 {After delivering the typical pawn break, Black is at least equal. We can continue by playing ...Rfc8 followed by the annoying ...a5-a4 ➼ poking White's queenside.} 
