6. Nxe5
7. dxe5
7. Bf5 {Black gets an easy game without having to remember much. We can just continue with ...e6 followed by ...Bc5-Ne7 generally, with a completely even position.} 
8. Bd3 {This is the most popular move for White, but not critical at all.8.Na3!?This is the only tricky idea that White has!8...Rc8!It is important to stay away from the ultra natural8...e6?because of9.Qa4+!and White gets a good position thanks to Nb5/Bb5 ideas.9.Be3e610.Nc2Ne711.Nd4Bg6Keeping the bishop pair.12.Be2Nc6=We are going to finish development with ...Be7 and ...O-O. Black's position is very safe.} 
8. Bxd3
9. Qxd3
9. e6
10. O-O
10. Qc7 {This is a cute move order, but there is also nothing wrong with10...Ne7!} 
11. Re1
11. Bc5
12. Nd2
12. Ne7
13. Nf3
13. O-O {We can continue with ...b5 followed by ...Rfc8 with the standard queenside play. A nice idea to keep in mind is ...Bb6 followed by ...Qc4 and if White accepts the queen trade, Black gets a lasting initiative in the endgame.} 
