7. Ne2 {This move gets played against me all the time. White's idea is to play Bf4 and gain a tempo by attacking our queen, but we can simply get rid of the knight and get a good position.7.Bf4??would be a huge blunder because we can mate on c1!7...Qxf48.Qxb7The idea is nice for White, but it doesn't quite work because of8...Qc1Checkmate ends the game. This is the quality information that you signed up for!} 
7. Bxe2 {Avoiding White's Bf4 ideas!} 
8. Bxe2 {White does not have any alternatives here because the cheeky8.Bf4??fails to8...Qxf49.Qxb7Bg4!(controlling the critical c8-square) and Black wins.} 
8. e6 {Preparing to play ...Bd6 next.} 
9. O-O {9.Nd2Nc610.Nf3Bd611.O-OO-O12.Bd3Ne4=We are ready to play ...f5 on the next move, while13.Bxe4dxe414.Ng5Bxh2+!is also fine for Black.} 
9. Bd6 {Threatening ...Bxh2+.} 
10. h3 {This is by far the most common move in online chess. I guess people are just afraid to play10.g3potentially because of10...h5!?.10.f4Nc611.Nd2O-OIt's important to stay away from11...Bxf4??12.Rxf4!and White wins.12.g3Rab8⇆We can continue with the minority attack by pushing ...b5-b4-bxc3. Black gets good pressure on the queenside with ...Rfc8-Ne7/Na5 type of ideas.10.g3Nc611.Nd2O-O =Going for safe play. If you want to experiment, there is an interesting idea to play11...h5followed by long castle, but it is definitely more double edged. After castling short, Black's main idea is to go for the typical minority attack with ...Rab8-b5 while you want to keep an eye on the ...e5-break when White plays Bd3 because our position could become really active.} 
10. O-O
11. Be3
11. Nc6
12. Nd2
12. h6 {This is just a nice move to have (stopping any Bg5 ideas).} 
13. Bd3
13. a6 {Preparing the ...b5-push.} 
14. Rfe1
14. Rfe8 {This is not a super standard idea, but after having given up the bishop pair so early in the game, I noticed the computer likes this idea of breaking with ...e5 whenever White has played Bd3 because after dxe5 we have ...Nxe5 coming with tempo.} 
15. Rac1
15. b5
16. Qd1
16. e5 {Black is getting very active in the upcoming IQP positions. For example, after17.dxe5Nxe518.Bf1Nc4!?is already quite annoying for White.} 
