6. Qc7 {The key point of the whole ...Nf6 and ...Bg4 move order! Normally the b7-pawn is defended with either ...Qd7 or ...Qc8, but in this particular case, White has not yet managed to play Bf4 which gives us this great opportunity to play ...Qc7 and take away this key square for White's dark-squared bishop!} 
7. h3 {The most critical line.} 
7. Bh5 {I consider the natural move to be the best. There is also an argument to be made for7...Bd7, but playing with the bishop locked inside the pawn chain might not be everyone's cup of tea.} 
8. g4 {This is the only real test for Black's set-up. I think generally this will be played by players over 2000 online rating because it requires move by move knowledge which is super uncommon for the general style of the 'Exchange Variation' which is known to be on the more positional side.8.Ne2This move was known to be pretty harmless until they discovered that8...Bxe2?!allows the powerful zwischenzug with9.Bf4!and Black is missing the key move after9...Qxf410.Qxb7we don't have the standard10...Bg4because of11.hxg4and White wins.8...Nc6I recommend we play this because the e2-knight is not ideally placed and Black gets a reasonable version.9.Bf4Qd710.Nd2e611.O-OBd6!This is important because taking the b7-pawn is usually quite risky for White!!12.Bxd6Qxd6and here White has two plans:A:13.Qxb7Rb814.Qa6Rxb2we are safely regaining the pawn and getting castled next move.B:13.Rfe1From my experience, this is more common.O-O14.a4Rab815.Ng3Bg6Once we get rid of the enemy light-squared bishop, we are generally safe.16.Bxg6hxg617.Nf3Qc7=This is the key move whenever White is threatening to play Ne5 so that we can immediately take it without allowing the fork. We can continue with moves like ...Rfc8-a6-b5 with pressure on the queenside.} 
8. Bg6
9. Bxg6
9. hxg6
10. g5 {This is a must after having played 8.g4.} 
10. Nfd7
11. Qxd5 {Here you can see the point behind White's previous play. For the time being, White has the extra pawn, but personally I feel like Black's position is easier to play because if White makes a small inaccuracy, their position could easily go downhill. From the games that I've seen, when Black makes a 'mistake' the refutation is generally not obvious at all.} 
11. e5 {I think striking in the center immediately is Black's best bet. The following positions are pretty difficult to navigate since there are less than 10 OTB games at the time I'm writing this, so I will just do my best to show what has been tried so far and what the computer thinks we need to be aware of.} 
12. Nf3 {Less accurate, but very natural.12.dxe5Na6!Preparing ...O-O-O and ...Nb4 ideas.13.e6O-O-O !!This is a beautiful illustration of Black's compensation.14.exd7+Rxd715.Qb5Nb4=∞White should be very careful in order to keep equality.} 
12. Nc6
13. Be3
13. O-O-O {Remembering the theory until here is quite critical. From this point White has a few alternatives:A)14.Qxf7exd415.Nxd4Nce5!16.Qe6Bc517.Nb5Qa5White needs to protect the b5-knight while ...Rhe8 is going to be really unpleasant to deal with.B)14.Qe4f5!15.gxf6gxf616.Qxg6Kb817.Nbd2exd418.cxd4Nb6We can continue with ...Nd5 next and despite the fact that we are down two pawns, Black is completely fine because White has no safe square for their king.C)14.Nbd2exd415.Nxd4Nc516.Qg2Nd3+17.Kf1Bc5with full compensation because White's pieces are stuck.} 
