[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Exchange Variation"]
[Black "4.Bd3 Nf6 5.h3 Nc6 6.c3 g6 7.Nf3 Bf5 with 8.Bxf5"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. exd5 {This is the traditional way of reaching the Exchange Variation. The important thing to know about this is that by learning the mainlines you will automatically have a very solid understanding which will also apply against the sidelines.For example, in lower rated games it is very common that White will start with move orders such as1.e4c62.Nf3d53.exd5or1.e4c62.Nc3d53.exd5or even1.e4c62.Bc4d53.exd5, which all can be placed into the same bucket of the 'Exchange Variation'. What I love about the Caro-Kann the most is that we can easily predict our opponent's moves, making it super easy to adapt.} 
3. cxd5
4. Bd3 {This is known to be White's most ambitious move. From my experience it becomes pretty common above 1800 online rating. Below 1800 they mainly do pretty goofy stuff like4.Nf3and then all kinds of weaker lines that we have covered in the previous lines.} 
4. Nf6 {It's very important to start this way! The idea is to meet5.c3with5...Bg4!} 
5. h3 {This is an interesting line for white, directed against the ...Bg4 lines. The main drawback of it is that the move h3 does not help White control the center, and Black can get a good version of the IQP after ...e5!} 
5. Nc6 {Threatening ...Nxd4!} 
6. c3 {Protecting the d4-pawn while stopping any ...Nb4 ideas.Against6.Nf3we can stick with the same6...g6which will most likely transpose.} 
6. g6 {This is the key idea to play with an active bishop. We are preparing to play ...Bf5 on the next move which is leading to a very interesting pawn structure.Another solid alternative is6...e5which leads to IQP positions where Black is completely fine as I showed in my Scandinavian Gambit course. The main reason why I decided to stick with6...g6is because from my experience, we could easily get a much better position after7.Nf3Bf58.Bxf5gxf5, and in general we keep the game interesting. The only drawback with 6...e5 is that it can become pretty hard to play for a win, and it's mainly meant to equalize.} 
7. Nf3
7. Bf5 {The whole point of our previous move! Please pay attention to the move order because once you play ...g6 it is very easy to enter auto-pilot mode and just fianchetto, so make sure to keep that in mind.} 
8. Bxf5 {This together with8.O-Oare the moves that we are going to see the most.8.Bxf5seems to be a very logical move because it creates doubled pawns for Black, but in reality I consider that to be a small mistake already! According to the computer, the position is still around equal, but White's moves will be far from intuitive. With natural moves, Black usually gets a pretty nice initiative on the kingside.} 
8. gxf5
9. O-O {9.Bf4This is the second most common move for White.9...Rg8Activating the rook and immediately targeting the g2-pawn.10.g3e6Preparing to play ...Bd6 which gets rid of White's most active piece.11.Nbd2Bd612.Bxd6Qxd613.Qe2Ne4=With an even position where I would definitely choose Black because of how active our position is. Whenever you get such a knight on e4 supported by the f5 and d5-pawns you will never lose! You can ask for a refund if that happens... (not really ;-) ).9.Bg5This is a common mistake because it overlooks Black's powerful reply.9...Ne4!This move can easily be missed by your opponents!10.Bf4Rg811.g3e612.Nbd2Bd6It's important to notice that Black is not rushing with ...Bg7. We generally prefer to develop the dark-squared bishop with ...e6-Bd6 because this is the most active square.13.Bxd6Qxd6⩱We can continue with long castle followed by ...f6-e5 ideas while constantly keeping an eye on the ...Nxg3 idea in case White makes the mistake to castle short.} 
9. Rg8 {This is a clever move order because we can meet10.Bg5with10...Ne4!when we gain a tempo compared to the normal lines.9...Bg7?!This is the result of auto-piloting! It doesn't lead to a losing position or anything like that, but it's missing the critical point. I want you to really understand that the bishop is not a great piece on g7 in this structure, simply because it's restricted by White's solid pawn chain (b2-c3-d4).} 
10. Bf4
10. e6 {Please notice that we are not really intending to fianchetto! I really want you to understand that it is very common for this variation to end up playing ...e6-Bd6 because it is simply a better square for the bishop. The key idea behind ...g6 is to make sure we manage to play without a bad light-squared bishop.} 
11. Nbd2
11. Bd6 {This way we are taking full advantage of our pawn structure. After this trade Black is in full control generally and has an easy path to a risk free initiative.} 
12. Bxd6 {12.Ne5The knight looks good for now, but it's just like a super expensive car (not really sustainable).12...Qc713.Ndf3Ne4⩱We have a huge threat of playing ...f6 on the next move. Generally Nxc6 will be answered by the intermezzo ...Bxf4! and White is in trouble. Another key idea after playing ...f6 is that we can transfer the queen by playing ...Qc7-Qg7! and White can get mated quite brutally.} 
12. Qxd6
13. Re1
13. Ne4 {This move is critical because we are not only centralizing and improving our own position, but also we manage to stop any activity by White related to Ne5 ideas.To get an idea of how difficult White's position is, we can think of the good old Romanian saying that goes something like 'A shepherd without animals is just a fool with a stick.' In our case this means that White simply has a passive position with no constructive plan to go for. Black can literally castle long, double rooks on the g-file and there is not much White can do about it.} 
