3. exd5 {This is the traditional way of reaching the Exchange Variation. The important thing to know about this is that by learning the mainlines you will automatically have a very solid understanding which will also apply against the sidelines.For example, in lower rated games it is very common that White will start with move orders such as1.e4c62.Nf3d53.exd5or1.e4c62.Nc3d53.exd5or even1.e4c62.Bc4d53.exd5, which all can be placed into the same bucket of the 'Exchange Variation'. What I love about the Caro-Kann the most is that we can easily predict our opponent's moves, making it super easy to adapt.} 
3. cxd5
4. Bd3 {This is known to be White's most ambitious move. From my experience it becomes pretty common above 1800 online rating. Below 1800 they mainly do pretty goofy stuff like4.Nf3and then all kinds of weaker lines that we have covered in the previous lines.} 
4. Nf6 {It's very important to start this way! The idea is to meet5.c3with5...Bg4!} 
5. h3 {This is an interesting line for white, directed against the ...Bg4 lines. The main drawback of it is that the move h3 does not help White control the center, and Black can get a good version of the IQP after ...e5!} 
5. Nc6 {Threatening ...Nxd4!} 
6. c3 {Protecting the d4-pawn while stopping any ...Nb4 ideas.Against6.Nf3we can stick with the same6...g6which will most likely transpose.} 
6. g6 {This is the key idea to play with an active bishop. We are preparing to play ...Bf5 on the next move which is leading to a very interesting pawn structure.Another solid alternative is6...e5which leads to IQP positions where Black is completely fine as I showed in my Scandinavian Gambit course. The main reason why I decided to stick with6...g6is because from my experience, we could easily get a much better position after7.Nf3Bf58.Bxf5gxf5, and in general we keep the game interesting. The only drawback with 6...e5 is that it can become pretty hard to play for a win, and it's mainly meant to equalize.} 
7. Nf3
7. Bf5 {The whole point of our previous move! Please pay attention to the move order because once you play ...g6 it is very easy to enter auto-pilot mode and just fianchetto, so make sure to keep that in mind.} 
8. O-O {This is White's best try, objectively speaking.} 
8. Bxd3 {At this point we don't have much of a choice. Please keep in mind that8...Bg7?!9.Bxf5!gxf5is leading to an improved version for White because the g7-bishop is misplaced in that structure.} 
9. Qxd3
9. Qc7 {This is the key move to remember! The standard9...Bg7allows10.Bf4with a slightly better position for White.} 
10. Re1 {This is what you are going to face the most.10.Ne5This move is super rare, but worth being aware of!10...Bg7!Accepting the pawn with10...Nxe511.dxe5Qxe5is too risky because of12.Qb5+.11.Bf4Nh5!The standard counter to Bf4!12.Bh2Nxe513.dxe5Bxe5!This time it's less risky to take on e5.14.Qb5+Kf815.Bxe5Qxe516.Nd2Nf4⩱0-1 Barsegian,A (2124)-Kozak,A (2315) Sochi Doroshkevich Amateur op 2017 (1). We are about to finish development with ...Kg7 and Black is perfectly fine.} 
10. Bg7 {Finally we are ready to fianchetto and castle short in the best version possible!} 
11. Ne5 {This is the most common move for White in my experience. White is simply preparing to play Bf4, which looks quite scary if you are not super familiar with these types of positions.11.Bg5Ne4=Whenever we can get this move, Black is fine. We can continue with ...O-O followed by ...f5 (supporting the e4-knight).11.Nbd2This is a pretty venomous move, used by Alekseev on many occasions.11...O-O12.Nb3Ne413.Ng5!?This is a very sneaky try.13...Nf6=This is a tough move to find, but the point is to simply play ...h6 followed by ...Ne4 with a fine position for Black.} 
11. O-O
12. Bf4
12. Nh5 {This is the key idea to neutralize White's play.} 
13. Bh2
13. Bxe5 {Not an easy move to find if you have no prior knowledge, but after doing a bit of research I came to the conclusion that the activity which we get in return should definitely compensate for giving up the precious fianchetto bishop.} 
14. dxe5 {The most ambitious move.14.Bxe5Nxe515.dxe5leads to a safe position for Black after all the trades.} 
14. Qb6 {Attacking the b2-pawn and preparing ...d4 ideas.} 
15. b3 {15.b4Nd8!!The computer comes up with this stunning maneuver!16.Qxd5Ne6=∞We can continue with ...Rfd8 followed by ...a5 with a very active position. Notice how the h2-bishop is really not doing much!15.Nd2Ng716.Nb3Rfd817.Bf4d4⇆With a very active position where the absence of the fianchettoed bishop is not felt, because the g7-knight is keeping our king really safe.} 
15. d4 {We can continue with ...Rfd8 followed by ...Ng7-Ne6 with a solid position.} 
