3. exd5 {This is the traditional way of reaching the Exchange Variation. The important thing to know about this is that by learning the mainlines you will automatically have a very solid understanding which will also apply against the sidelines.For example, in lower rated games it is very common that White will start with move orders such as1.e4c62.Nf3d53.exd5or1.e4c62.Nc3d53.exd5or even1.e4c62.Bc4d53.exd5, which all can be placed into the same bucket of the 'Exchange Variation'. What I love about the Caro-Kann the most is that we can easily predict our opponent's moves, making it super easy to adapt.} 
3. cxd5
4. c3 {This is a very rare move order for the Caro-Kann, but we have to be prepared against everything! The idea is to play Bf4 next and transpose to the London System (put the moves d4, Bf4, c3, e3 on the board and insert the capture ...c5xd4/e3xd4 and you get the same position).The only reason why this is slightly annoying is the fact that against 4. Bd3 we are playing a very concrete line, which makes it impossible to transpose when White deviates like this. The good news is that we have a great counter with little theory to know!} 
4. Bf5
5. Qb3 {I consider this to be the only 'dangerous' move that we need to be prepared for.5.Bf4Normal play is not really challenging to deal with.5...Nc66.Nf3e67.Nbd2Bd68.Bxd6Qxd69.Nh4This is White's only ambitious try.9...Nf6!?The computer likes this idea, but there is nothing really wrong with 9...Bg6!10.Nxf5exf511.Bd3g612.O-OO-O =Despite having an isolated pawn, Black is very active and we could continue with ...Rae8-h5-Kg7 and eventually use ...Ne4 ideas.} 
5. Qd7
6. Nf3
6. Nc6 {Stopping Ne5 ideas.} 
7. Bf4
7. f6 {This is the nice part about having delayed the move ...Nf6! Black is able to get full control over the most important square of the London System.} 
8. Nbd2
8. g5 {This idea is incredibly annoying for White. They simply have no way to punish it, while Black is getting a nice push on the kingside.} 
9. Bg3
9. h5
10. h3
10. e6
11. Be2
11. Nge7
12. O-O
12. Bg6 {Preparing to play ...Nf5!} 
13. Rfe1
13. Nf5
14. Bd3
14. Kf7 {Protecting the g6-bishop while the king is pretty safe on this square. Next up we have the concrete threat of ...Nxg3, while ...g4 ideas should not be underestimated because Black can get a pretty dangerous attack!} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Exchange Variation"]
[Black "4.c3 Bf5! with 7.Bb5"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. exd5 {This is the traditional way of reaching the Exchange Variation. The important thing to know about this is that by learning the mainlines you will automatically have a very solid understanding which will also apply against the sidelines.For example, in lower rated games it is very common that White will start with move orders such as1.e4c62.Nf3d53.exd5or1.e4c62.Nc3d53.exd5or even1.e4c62.Bc4d53.exd5, which all can be placed into the same bucket of the 'Exchange Variation'. What I love about the Caro-Kann the most is that we can easily predict our opponent's moves, making it super easy to adapt.} 
3. cxd5
4. c3 {This is a very rare move order for the Caro-Kann, but we have to be prepared against everything! The idea is to play Bf4 next and transpose to the London System (put the moves d4, Bf4, c3, e3 on the board and insert the capture ...c5xd4/e3xd4 and you get the same position).The only reason why this is slightly annoying is the fact that against 4. Bd3 we are playing a very concrete line, which makes it impossible to transpose when White deviates like this. The good news is that we have a great counter with little theory to know!} 
4. Bf5
5. Qb3 {I consider this to be the only 'dangerous' move that we need to be prepared for.5.Bf4Normal play is not really challenging to deal with.5...Nc66.Nf3e67.Nbd2Bd68.Bxd6Qxd69.Nh4This is White's only ambitious try.9...Nf6!?The computer likes this idea, but there is nothing really wrong with 9...Bg6!10.Nxf5exf511.Bd3g612.O-OO-O =Despite having an isolated pawn, Black is very active and we could continue with ...Rae8-h5-Kg7 and eventually use ...Ne4 ideas.} 
5. Qd7
6. Nf3
6. Nc6 {Stopping Ne5 ideas.} 
7. Bb5 {Pinning the c6-knight and creating a direct threat of going Ne5!7.Ne5This has been tried a decent amount, but Black has an easy fix.7...Nxe58.dxe5a6=Stopping White's only threat of going Bb5! After this we are going to finish development with ...e6-Bc5-Ne7 followed by ...O-O, with an easy game.} 
7. f6 {Remember this key idea to stop White's only threat.} 
8. O-O
8. e6
9. Re1
9. a6
10. Bxc6
10. Qxc6
11. Nh4
11. Ne7 {While you can make an argument for keeping the bishop, I think development should be prioritized.} 
12. Nxf5
12. Nxf5
13. Nd2
13. Kf7 {Don't be shy to play this move! The king is quite safe while protecting the important e6-square.} 
14. Nf3
14. Bd6 {We can continue with ...Rag8 followed by the kingside storm connected with ...g5-h5-g4-h4 (ultimately breaking with ...g3!).} 
