[Black "Classical Variation: Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. Nc3 {The starting position for the Classical Variation. Please keep in mind that 3.Nd2 will simply transpose!} 
3. dxe4
4. Nxe4
4. Nf6
5. Nxf6+ {This is the mainline, which you are going to face the most.5.Ng3This is the most common way for White to avoid the Tartakower, however we also mention some other less popular alternatives in the Informational.5...g66.Nf3Bg7⇆Make sure to play ...c5 on the very next move and Black is completely ok! For more details check out the trainables.} 
5. exf6 {White is now at a crossroads.} 
6. Nf3 {This is what I expect you to face the most below 1800.6.c3In case your opponent is wearing a suit, there's a good chance they will find this move, but I would really expect it from someone above 2200 generally.6...Bd67.Bd3O-O8.Qc2Re8+9.Ne2h6This is the key move for our repertoire! For more details make sure to check out the trainables. (Don't touch this variation if you are below 1800, you are too young to understand it.)} 
6. Bd6
7. Bd3
7. O-O {At this point White pretty much has a choice between two plans:‣Most of the times they will castle short by playing8.O-O‣The rebels will try8.Be3Re89.Qd2➼ preparing O-O-O where the key move for Black is9...Na6!} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Classical Variation"]
[Black "Tartakower 6.Nf3 & 7.Bd3 with 10.c3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. Nc3 {The Classical variation. This used to be very trendy around 2014 after Negi Parimarjan published his revolutionary 1.e4 series (in his book, the move order is3.Nd2, which generally leads to the same thing)! However, in the maintime, neural network engines were developed and together with Leela Zero, the Caro-Kann has started to catch up again!} 
3. dxe4 {This is the only serious move. If you are looking for fun (but pretty terrible) sidelines, you can try3...a6!?and3...b5on your own risk!} 
4. Nxe4
4. Nf6 {The Tartakower! This is by far my favorite move and the easiest answer to the Classical Variation.There is nothing really wrong with4...Bf5, other than the fact that the theory is pretty heavy and the games are generally hard to win for Black. If you are looking for interesting alternatives, you could keep an eye on4...h6or4...Qc7!?, but that is not really why we have gathered here!} 
5. Nxf6+
5. exf6
6. Nf3 {This is what lower rated players do. If you are below 2000 I really expect you to face this the most!} 
6. Bd6
7. Bd3 {This is usually the most common way for White to develop their bishop.} 
7. O-O
8. O-O
8. Bg4
9. h3
9. Bh5 {We always step back in the Tartakower (unless we can double the pawns).} 
10. c3 {This is by far the most common move for online chess and it is not even close!} 
10. Re8 {This is the most flexible move. While there is nothing wrong with the most common move10...Nd7➼ I prefer10...Re8because it is setting up a pretty nasty positional trap in case White goes11.Re1?Rxe1+!12.Qxe1Bxf3!13.gxf3with a compromised pawn structure for White which usually gives us a large advantage because White's king will be very vulnerable in the long run.} 
11. Be3
11. Nd7 {Preparing the thematic maneuver with ...Nf8!} 
12. Re1
12. Nf8 {This is the most confusing part for a lot of the newer players. I mean -WHAT IS THE KNIGHT DOING ON F8? I DON'T GET IT!- If I gained 1 elo point everytime I heard this question, Magnus Carlsen would have been in danger! On a more serious note, Black is preparing ...Ng6/Ne6 ideas while also making room for the standard battery with ...Bc7-Qd6. I hope that makes sense!} 
13. Be2 {White's position is pretty difficult to play and they usually do something about the annoying pin (even when it loses a tempo).} 
13. Bc7 {THIS IS THE MOST IMPORTANT IDEA that you want to remember from the Tartakower. Because of this, Black is usually able to get a lot of attacking chances against the enemy king.} 
14. Qd2
14. Qd6 {Creating a threat of ...Bxf3 followed by ...Qh2+! Personally I think you can stop here with the memorization and should be okay, but the following lines are very common and truly show Black's attacking potential. At this point White has two main options:A)15.Rad1Bxf316.Bxf3Qh2+17.Kf1f5!B)15.g3Qd7!This is the key move that a lot of my students usually have problems finding. However this is a pretty logical move because the diagonal has been just restricted and White had ideas of playing Bf4 ➼ exchanging more pieces and reducing Black's attacking potential (on top of that we are also attacking the h3-pawn). Now White has a choice between:B1)16.g4??Bxg4!17.hxg4Qxg4+18.Kf1Qh3+19.Kg1Re4!With ...Rg4 coming on the next move, white is about to get brutally mated.B2)16.Kg2Bg6!17.b4Be4!18.a4Ng619.a5f520.Rad1f4!21.gxf4Nh4+!22.Kg3Nxf323.Bxf3Bxf324.Kxf3Qxh3+25.Ke2Bxf4This may look pretty crazy because we are 25 moves deep. From my experience I shown this plan to a lot of players around 1000 elo strength, and they were able to recreate this whole sequence quite easily.Now clearly you don't need to rememebr every single move to go out and play this variation, but I hope this gives you a nice view of the dynamic potential that Black has in this variation.} 
