1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. Nc3 {The Classical variation. This used to be very trendy around 2014 after Negi Parimarjan published his revolutionary 1.e4 series (in his book, the move order is3.Nd2, which generally leads to the same thing)! However, in the maintime, neural network engines were developed and together with Leela Zero, the Caro-Kann has started to catch up again!} 
3. dxe4 {This is the only serious move. If you are looking for fun (but pretty terrible) sidelines, you can try3...a6!?and3...b5on your own risk!} 
4. Nxe4
4. Nf6 {The Tartakower! This is by far my favorite move and the easiest answer to the Classical Variation.There is nothing really wrong with4...Bf5, other than the fact that the theory is pretty heavy and the games are generally hard to win for Black. If you are looking for interesting alternatives, you could keep an eye on4...h6or4...Qc7!?, but that is not really why we have gathered here!} 
5. Nxf6+
5. exf6
6. Nf3 {This is what lower rated players do. If you are below 2000 I really expect you to face this the most!} 
6. Bd6
7. Bd3 {This is usually the most common way for White to develop their bishop.} 
7. O-O
8. O-O
8. Bg4
9. h3
9. Bh5 {We always step back in the Tartakower (unless we can double the pawns).} 
10. g4 {This is a common reaction for players below 1500. The interesting part is that the computer thinks this move is perfectly okay objectively speaking, and the position should remain close to equal. In reality I consider this to be a pretty significant weakening of White's king, and based on my experience, the position will be much trickier for White to play than for Black. Usually the evaluation will turn into Black's favor in the following 5-10 moves.} 
10. Bg6
11. Bxg6 {This is usually what follows after White plays the aggressive g4.11.Nh4Bc7!?Setting up the battery works even better than finishing development first here because we are trying to exploit the missing f3-knight.12.Nf5?!Bxf5!Getting rid of the annoying knight.13.Bxf5Qd614.f4Re815.c3Nd7⩱We can continue with ...Nf8-Ne6 with a slight edge because White's kingside is overextended.11.c3This is also something that I faced online during the rating climbs.11...Re812.Be3Nd713.Qc2Even though this position is nothing special really, I wanted to share with you the following cool trick!13...Bxd314.Qxd3Nc5!Activating the knight with tempo because of the little discovery.15.Qc2Ne6⩱With a comfortable position for us and it is not clear why White overextended their position.} 
11. hxg6 {We could  stop at this point and claim that the 'pawn cube' is a forced win, but for the sake of this course and in order not to get fired, I need to go a little bit deeper than that. Jokes aside, in this structure Black's king is ultra safe while White has created a bunch of weak squares on the kingside (especially f4).} 
12. c3
12. Re8 {This is always a good move.} 
13. Be3
13. Nd7 {Preparing the standard ...Nf8!} 
14. Qd2
14. Nf8 {Preparing ...g5 followed by ...Ng6-Nf4 ideas (exploiting White's weakest square).} 
15. Rfe1 {15.Bf4?This seems to be a common mistake for online games.15...Bxf416.Qxf4Re2-+Black will win a pawn soon because the rook is too active.} 
15. g5 {Fixing the weak square on f4 while preparing ...Ng6-Nf4!} 
16. Rad1
16. Ng6 {With a slight edge for Black. The following line is quite instructive:17.d5Qc7!18.dxc6Rad8!and Black is better!} 
