3. dxe4 {This is the only serious move. If you are looking for fun (but pretty terrible) sidelines, you can try3...a6!?and3...b5on your own risk!} 
4. Nxe4
4. Nf6 {The Tartakower! This is by far my favorite move and the easiest answer to the Classical Variation.There is nothing really wrong with4...Bf5, other than the fact that the theory is pretty heavy and the games are generally hard to win for Black. If you are looking for interesting alternatives, you could keep an eye on4...h6or4...Qc7!?, but that is not really why we have gathered here!} 
5. Nxf6+
5. exf6
6. Nf3 {This is what lower rated players do. If you are below 2000 I really expect you to face this the most!} 
6. Bd6
7. Bd3 {This is usually the most common way for White to develop their bishop.} 
7. O-O
8. O-O
8. Bg4
9. h3
9. Bh5 {We always step back in the Tartakower (unless we can double the pawns).} 
10. Re1 {This is the most accurate move for White, taking control of the open file.} 
10. Nd7 {This is the most natural move. An interesting alternative could be10...Bc711.c3Qd612.g3Na613.Bf4Qd714.Bxc7Nxc715.Kg2Rfe8with a balanced position.} 
11. c3 {This is the most common move. In case of11.c4I recommend11...Rc812.Be3Bb813.Be2Qc714.g3Rfe815.Bf4Qb616.Bxb8Rxb8with an equal position.} 
11. Re8 {Challenging the open file is best, objectively speaking.However,11...Rc8could be an interesting alternative (preparing the battery). A sample line is12.Be3Bb813.Be2Qc714.g3Rfe815.Bf4Qb616.Bxb8Rxb817.Qd2Nf8with a balanced game.} 
12. Rxe8+
12. Qxe8
13. Be3
13. Rd8 {Placing the rook behind the enemy queen is like you just went out, but the very first second your parents start calling... The enemy queen can hardly have a good time now until it switches the file!} 
14. Be2
14. Nb6 {Usually I am a big partisan of going ...Nf8, but in this case, this move is simply too strong because Black has a strong positional threat of playing ...Nd5!} 
15. Nd2 {This is the safest move for White. You may be wondering if White can try to stop our little idea by playing the move15.c4, but then15...Bxf3!should be good enough. White gets a ruined pawn structure or simply drops the c4-pawn!} 
15. Bxe2
16. Qxe2
16. f5 {Never play ...f6! ➼ so ...f5 should be good! (threatening to win a piece with ...f4 among other things)} 
17. Qf3
17. Qe6 {We can continue to improve our position with moves such as ...Re8-Nd5-g6 with equality at the very least.} 
