2. d5
3. Nc3 {The Classical variation. This used to be very trendy around 2014 after Negi Parimarjan published his revolutionary 1.e4 series (in his book, the move order is3.Nd2, which generally leads to the same thing)! However, in the maintime, neural network engines were developed and together with Leela Zero, the Caro-Kann has started to catch up again!} 
3. dxe4 {This is the only serious move. If you are looking for fun (but pretty terrible) sidelines, you can try3...a6!?and3...b5on your own risk!} 
4. Nxe4
4. Nf6 {The Tartakower! This is by far my favorite move and the easiest answer to the Classical Variation.There is nothing really wrong with4...Bf5, other than the fact that the theory is pretty heavy and the games are generally hard to win for Black. If you are looking for interesting alternatives, you could keep an eye on4...h6or4...Qc7!?, but that is not really why we have gathered here!} 
5. Nxf6+
5. exf6
6. Nf3 {This is what lower rated players do. If you are below 2000 I really expect you to face this the most!} 
6. Bd6
7. Bc4 {This variation is quite similar to7.Bd3, which made me skip it from the trainable section. You can literally play the same way as against7.Bd3, plus you get a very decent option to go for the universal plan that's always annyoing for Bc4 lines: ...Na6-Nc7 followed by ...Be6 ➼ neutralizing the c4-bishop.7.Be2This line is quite rare, but definitely makes sense because it's making ...Bg4 less effective. There are basically two ways you can play this:A) if you are below 1500 I would recommend to play the same way vs all7.Be27.Bd3and7.Bc4for the sake of simplicity;B) once you start climbing the ladder you can develop the usual way, but instead of ...Bg4 play with ...Be6/Bf5.   Play might continue7...O-O8.O-ORe8Controlling the open file is always a good idea!9.Re1Nd710.c3Nf811.Be3Ng612.Qd2Be6=With a very solid position for Black. You can choose between at least two interesting plans: A) ...Bc7-Qd6 with pressure against the white king; B) ...Qc7-Rad8 followed by ...Nf4 ideas and White most likely has to give up the bishop pair leading to a pleasant position for Black.7.h3This move freaks out the less experienced players because they are married to the ...Bg4 idea and all of a sudden they feel quite lonely. Jokes aside, I need to make you understand that we should be happy once we see h3 on the board! I mean, if it did not last you were probably not supposed to be together in the first place... Okay I will stop with the nonsense! Long story short, the h3-pawn will become a target as shown in line B on move 12.7...O-O8.Bd3Re8+9.Be3Nd7!There is no need to enter the rabbit hole starting after 9...Bf4.10.O-ONf811.c3Be6This is a standard way to develop for Black when both ...Bg4 and ...Bf5 are not available. Now White has a choice between:A)12.Re1Bc7!13.Qc2Qd6with a huge threat of playing ...Bd5 (eliminating the f3-knight) and ...Ng6-Nh4 ideas.B)12.Qc2Qd7!and Black gets a very promising position with ...Bxh3 coming soon!} 
7. O-O
8. O-O {Now Black has a choice between two very reasonable plans:A)8...Bg4with similar play to 7.Bd3 lines;B)8...Na6followed by ...Nc7-Be6 shutting down the c4-bishop, with a balanced game.} 
