[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. Nc3 {The Classical variation. This used to be very trendy around 2014 after Negi Parimarjan published his revolutionary 1.e4 series (in his book, the move order is3.Nd2, which generally leads to the same thing)! However, in the maintime, neural network engines were developed and together with Leela Zero, the Caro-Kann has started to catch up again!} 
3. dxe4 {This is the only serious move. If you are looking for fun (but pretty terrible) sidelines, you can try3...a6!?and3...b5on your own risk!} 
4. Nxe4
4. Nf6 {The Tartakower! This is by far my favorite move and the easiest answer to the Classical Variation.There is nothing really wrong with4...Bf5, other than the fact that the theory is pretty heavy and the games are generally hard to win for Black. If you are looking for interesting alternatives, you could keep an eye on4...h6or4...Qc7!?, but that is not really why we have gathered here!} 
5. Nxf6+
5. exf6
6. Bc4 {This could be a challenging move order (especially if unprepared).} 
6. Bd6
7. Qe2+ {This is the main point behind the 6.Bc4 move order. Now Black is lacking the ideal move (...Be6) to block the check.7.Qh5This strange sideline does not really change much.7...O-O8.Ne2Na6!We can stick with the standard plan against Bc4 lines by simply going ...Na6-Nc7-Be6 with a solid game.9.O-ONc710.c3Be611.Bd3g6Once again avoiding the very sneaky threat of checkmate in one move.12.Qh4Re813.Nf4Bd7=Keeping the bishop pair. We are ready to play ...Ne6 on the next move with a solid position.} 
7. Be7 {I find this to be the best practical move, because we are keeping dynamic potential by avoiding the queen trade and it is not like the dark-squared bishop will always stay on e7. You can think of it as a quick stop to get some food and water before we make it to the final destination on d6!Experienced Grandmasters have also tried7...Qe78.Qxe7+Kxe79.Ne2, but I simply do not understand why would we enter this type of endgame where realistically speaking only White can win and they don't really face any risks. Sure, you can make the argument that according to the stats, Black seems to be doing just fine, but it is simply against our general strategy of trying to compensate for the doubled pawns with dynamics.On the other hand I also tried to make7...Kf8!?work, but I would not really recommend it. If White finds/knows8.Qh5!Black's position becomes pretty uncomfortable, since one of the main ideas is to push ...h5 and activate the rook that way.} 
8. Nf3
8. O-O
9. O-O
9. Bd6 {Placing the bishop on the ideal square.} 
10. Re1
10. Na6 {This is the universal reply to Bc4-lines. We are preparing ...Nc7 and then we could either go for ...Be6 or ...Nd5!} 
11. Bxa6 {This is always the most ambtious move for White, but generally should be pretty harmless.11.Bd2was recently played in a pretty high profile game which followed11...Nc712.Qd3a5!?13.a4Nd514.c3Be615.Bb3Qd716.h3Bf517.Qf1h5!18.Bd1g5!and Black took over the initiative in the game between Ivanchuk-Duda, 2022.} 
