13. Ng3 {With multiple annoying threats such as Nf5 immediately or simply playing f4-f5! Let's look at some other possibilities too:A)13.Nf4Creating a big positional threat of winning the light squared bishop.13...Bxf4!This is a much better way of losing the bishop pair than allowing Nxe6, because we keep better control over the center (since the queen is directly watching the d4-square), while we still have the typical idea to play ...b5 and fix the queenside.14.Bxf4Qd7=We can simply continue with ...Rad8 followed by ...b5 or even sacrificing the pawn with ...Ng6 because Black is getting very active in the upcoming endgames (at least that's what the computer thinks).B)13.f4This plan could simply be devastating if you allow White to play f5 followed by Bf4 with a simple and deadly initiative.13...c5!This is the computer's favorite move to get counterplay. The point is to put pressure in the center and be able to meet Bf4 with ...Bc6!13...f5!?This move also gives us somewhat decent compensation. In any case, it is much better than playing something passive.14.Bxf5Bxf515.Qxf5Qb616.b3c5=∞With very decent play for the pawn considering the fact that ...Qa6 can sometimes win it back immediately (and we managed to avoid a monster attack).14.f5Bd715.Bf4Bc6=With adequate counterplay. Keep in mind that one of White's typical ideas is something like16.Bxd6Qxd617.Rf4(preparing Rg4 with annoying pressure), but in this version17...Rxe2!is quite the killer move.C)13.c4Qd7This move is pretty sensible because 13...Qc7 14.c5 could be annoying.14.Bc3Bc7In case White does nothing critical, we are ready to play ...Rad8 followed by ...b5-Bb6 with an active position.15.f4Bg4= We are ready to continue with ...Bxe2 next followed by ...Ne6 with a solid position for Black.} 
13. c5 {It is not very common to play this move in the Tartakower, but when White has so many pieces on the kingside we need to strike in the center not to get mated!} 
14. Bb5 {This may seem a bit uncomfortable to deal with.14.Nf5cxd415.Nxd4Qc716.h3Rad817.Nxe6Nxe6=With the knight on e6 we never lose, hear me out! Black is too active, which compensates us for not having the bishop pair.} 
14. Re7
15. Nf5
15. Bxf5
16. Qxf5
16. Qb6 {This is the key move to keep a balanced game. We are exploiting the awkward position of White's bishop.} 
17. Rxe7
17. Bxe7
18. Qd3
18. cxd4 {Creating an isolated pawn.} 
19. cxd4
19. Rd8
20. Be3
20. Ne6 {With the knight on e6 we never lose!} 
