4. Nf6 {The Tartakower! This is by far my favorite move and the easiest answer to the Classical Variation.There is nothing really wrong with4...Bf5, other than the fact that the theory is pretty heavy and the games are generally hard to win for Black. If you are looking for interesting alternatives, you could keep an eye on4...h6or4...Qc7!?, but that is not really why we have gathered here!} 
5. Nxf6+
5. exf6
6. c3 {This is known to be the most precise move order for White, which generally gets played in games over 2000 (it's rare below that). The point is to defend the d4-pawn in order to play Bd3 followed by Qc2 with O-O-O ideas. However, recently it turns out that even in this move order ➼ the O-O plans are a bit more annoying to deal with (maybe it's just me because the other lines are just so much more fun to play as Black!).} 
6. Bd6
7. Bd3
7. O-O
8. Qc2
8. Re8+
9. Ne2
9. h6 {This is a bit of a forgotten variation. There is of course, nothing wrong with the trendy9...h5, but I just prefer our little approach so much more because against the long castle lines I was able to find a stunning novelty, and against the O-O lines it feels like the h6-pawn is a bit safer compared to the9...h5lines. I definitely recommend you to try out both, but from personal experience I find9...h6so much easier to play and would really recommend it especially for players below 2200 (above that it's good to have both in your repertoire).} 
10. Be3 {This is the most common move for White, preparing to castle long.} 
10. Nd7
11. O-O-O
11. f5 {The first time I saw this move, I was like 'WTF is going on?! How could this ever be a good idea?' It looks like Black is literally hanging a pawn while not getting anything in exchange.However... The truth is that this crazy novelty works insanely well against 10.Be3 because ...Nf6-Nd5 comes with a tempo.} 
12. Bxf5 {This is the most natural move and what I expect you to face the most. If White simply refuses to take the 'free pawn' the game could go something like12.Rhe1Nf613.h3Be6!14.Kb1Nd5and Black is very comfortable.} 
12. Nf6 {Preparing to play ...Nd5 next ➼ putting pressure on the e3-bishop. Now White has a choice.} 
13. Ng3
13. Bxg3 {This is a very concrete approach, but works quite well.} 
14. hxg3
14. Qd5 {Attacking both a2 and g2.} 
15. Bxc8
15. Raxc8
16. a3
16. Ng4 {White has to be careful now to keep equality.} 
