6. Be3 {This is an interesting move for White that became reasonably popular at the top level recently. The top GMs mainly use it to play Bd3 followed by Ne2 (without dropping the d4-pawn as after 6.Bd3). For online games I noticed White players do this with the idea to play Qd2 and O-O-O, leading to unbalanced positions that should generally be good for Black!6.Bf4This is of course, not very critical, but it gets played sometimes especially in online games.6...Bd67.Qd2O-O8.O-O-OBe6Threatening to collect the a2-pawn.9.Kb1b5=With a pretty unbalanced position, but clearly very playable for us. A simply plan could be ...Na6-Nc7-Nd5 and then focus on queenside play.6.Bd3!?This pawn sacrifice is quite new, but pretty interesting as a surprise weapon. It was tried occassionaly at the top level, but from my experience people who do this online just blunder the d4-pawn (LOL).6...Qxd4It is possible to decline the pawn sacrifice, but I think taking can even put us ahead!7.Nf3Qd5!Even better than the safer ...Qd8 move!8.O-OBe69.Re1Nd7!Playing for ...O-O-O turns out to be incredibly effective.10.Qe2?!This is a slight mistake, but Black has nothing to worry about even after the better move10.Bf4Nc5!with at least an equal game.10...O-O-O⩱With a slight edge for Black according to the engine (thanks to the extra pawn).6.Qe2+This is a common mistake for the lower rated players. Usually the 'thinking process' is something like -I see check, I give check!-6...Be6I like this move a bit better because we are keeping options to play ...Bd6 followed by ...O-O with quick development.7.Nf3Bd68.Be3O-O9.O-O-O ?This is a very common mistake.9...Bxa2∓This works really well because on10.b3the move10...Qa5!just wins for Black because the a2-bishop is immortal!} 
