[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. Nc3 {The Classical variation. This used to be very trendy around 2014 after Negi Parimarjan published his revolutionary 1.e4 series (in his book, the move order is3.Nd2, which generally leads to the same thing)! However, in the maintime, neural network engines were developed and together with Leela Zero, the Caro-Kann has started to catch up again!} 
3. dxe4 {This is the only serious move. If you are looking for fun (but pretty terrible) sidelines, you can try3...a6!?and3...b5on your own risk!} 
4. Nxe4
4. Nf6 {The Tartakower! This is by far my favorite move and the easiest answer to the Classical Variation.There is nothing really wrong with4...Bf5, other than the fact that the theory is pretty heavy and the games are generally hard to win for Black. If you are looking for interesting alternatives, you could keep an eye on4...h6or4...Qc7!?, but that is not really why we have gathered here!} 
5. Ng3 {This is the most common way for White to avoid the Tartakower. From my experience and according to the stats, you will face this about 1/4 games!} 
5. g6 {This is my favorite move because the ...g6-pawn is restricting the g3-knight quite nicely. The main reason for doing this type of 'unusual' set-up for the Caro-Kann is that5...Bg46.f3leads to strange positions, since it is not easy to find a good place for the light squared bishop.Other playable options are:5...h5(best according to the computer, but leading to very strange lines),5...c5(a bit too concrete for my taste),5...e5(definitely fine, but quite dull), and5...e6(tricky to play with the passive bishop).} 
6. Nf3
6. Bg7
7. Bd3 {This is the most common move for online games, but the d3-bishop is not looking very impressive staring into the g6-pawn. Usually such a piece can be compared to a deadly sniper, but thanks to the solid block of pawns h7-g6-f7, it looks like the d3-bishop instead of a gun is holding a banana!} 
7. c5 {While the simpler play with7...O-O8.O-OBg4works well here, I think it is a bit easier to remember just to play ...c5 immediately after ...Bg7 against all of White's options.} 
8. dxc5
8. O-O
9. O-O
9. Nbd7 {This is the key idea to regain the pawn in THE BEST version possible. The knight will be very active on c5!} 
10. Be3
10. Nd5 {This is a common way to make sure that White is unable to keep the extra pawn! We have a double threat of ...Bxb2 and ...Nxe2 followed by ...Nxc5 which are impossible to stop.} 
