7. Bc4 {This is the most dangerous move, but as long as you remember the key idea to play ...c5 right after ...Bg7 ➼ Black can be pretty optimistic about the future.7.c3c5!Sticking with the typical idea. Sacrificing the pawn for now, but the point is that White will have a hard time coordinating!8.dxc5The other moves simply give Black an easy game after ...cxd4!8...Qxd1+9.Kxd1Nbd7!10.Bb5The only move that keeps the extra pawn.10...O-O11.c6bxc612.Bxc6Rb8Preparing to play ...Rb6 which will most likely secure us the bishop pair.13.Kc2Rb614.Bxd7Nxd7=∞Taking back with the bishop was also reasonable, but this is even stronger because we are preparing to push in the center with ...e5-f5-e4! This could easily give us a much better position, and I find it very tricky to handle as White.7.h3Stopping ...Bg4 ideas, but not really countering our main plan.7...c5!Now going dxc5 is even less appealing for White because we can easily regain the pawn.8.c3cxd49.Nxd4O-O10.Be2a6!This is a very useful move preparing to play ...Qc7 without allowing any annoying Nb5 ideas.11.O-ONbd712.a4Qc713.a5Nc5=We can continue with ...Rd8 and ...e5 with a completely fine position for Black.} 
