1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. Nc3 {The Classical variation. This used to be very trendy around 2014 after Negi Parimarjan published his revolutionary 1.e4 series (in his book, the move order is3.Nd2, which generally leads to the same thing)! However, in the maintime, neural network engines were developed and together with Leela Zero, the Caro-Kann has started to catch up again!} 
3. dxe4 {This is the only serious move. If you are looking for fun (but pretty terrible) sidelines, you can try3...a6!?and3...b5on your own risk!} 
4. Nxe4
4. Nf6 {The Tartakower! This is by far my favorite move and the easiest answer to the Classical Variation.There is nothing really wrong with4...Bf5, other than the fact that the theory is pretty heavy and the games are generally hard to win for Black. If you are looking for interesting alternatives, you could keep an eye on4...h6or4...Qc7!?, but that is not really why we have gathered here!} 
5. Ng5 {This is not really a dangerous continuation, but strong players have gone for it from time to time.5.Qd3!?This is a pretty trendy sideline at the top level recently. It is nothing special, but a try to avoid the Tartakower structure and get a relatively fresh position (hoping to outplay their opponent later). This is what I would asume at least!5...Nxe4While there are many ways to deal with this, I think going directly for the endgame should be the easiest fix.6.Qxe4Qd5!This is a typical idea for the Caro-Kann Defense! Generally speaking we are happy trading pieces and keeping a solid position.7.Bd3This is the top move of the engine.I would not go into too much detail here, because it is simply a super rare line and I don't want you to focus on ultra situational spots. However, it is worth mentioning that7.Qxd5cxd5is completely fine for Black with a structure that we normally get from the exchange variation where Black should go for the minority attack.7...Qxe4+8.Bxe4It's hard to believe that this endgame could be problematic for Black, but it does look a little more pleasant for White (if Leela is handling the White pieces).8...g6!?This is a nice way to develop while keeping the light-squared bishop active. The main problem is that ...Bg4 is often vulnerable to Nf3-Ne5 ideas, while 8...e6 is simply a bit too passive for my taste (even tho I am aware of the fact that many experienced Caro-Kann players would be more than happy to defend that position).9.Nf3Bg710.c3O-O11.O-Oa5!?With the idea to play ...a4 and grab space on the queenside.12.a4Be6!?This looks a bit artificial, but works quite well.13.Re1Nd714.h3Rfe8Making sure the e7-pawn is well protected and potentially preparing ideas to break with ...e5! in the future.15.Bf4Bc4=With a balanced endgame.5.Nc3I got this occasionally too, but it definitely does not pose any problems.5...Bf5Getting the bishop outside the pawn chain before playing ...e6!6.Nf3e67.Bd3Bxd38.Qxd3Nbd79.O-OBe710.Bf4O-O11.Rfe1Qa5=We can continue with ...Rfd8-Rac8 followed by ...Qh5-Qg6 with a completely fine position.5.Nc5This is quite rare and not critical by any means, but the 'refutation' is quite instructive!5...e5!Forcing equality.6.dxe5Qxd1+7.Kxd1Bxc58.exf6gxf6=With an even endgame, because White is struggling to coordinate his pieces.5.Bd3I would dare to say that this is a common 'mistake' for lower rated players! Now the funny thing is that according to the engine, this is a pretty interesting pawn sacrifice, but in reality most players who end up playing this are simply blundering their d4-pawn. The main reason for me to say that is that it usually becomes pretty clear in the following 5 moves that White fails to find the optimal moves, and Black simply ends up with an extra pawn.5...Qxd4!Calling White's bluff. A lot of my students tend to overlook this move, so you really want to pay attention!6.Nf3Qd5While there is nothing wrong with 6...Qd8, this move is even better! Now White has a choice between:A)7.Nxf6+exf68.O-OBe69.Re1Nd710.Qe2O-O-Owith a slight edge for Black;B)7.c4Qd88.Nxf6+exf69.O-OBe610.Re1Bb4!11.Re2O-Owith a balanced position, but I prefer Black in the long run with the extra pawn.} 
5. h6
