[White "5) Two Knights Variation"]
[Black "Two Knights: Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. Nc3
2. d5
3. Nf3 {This is the starting position for the so called 'Two Knights' variation. I consider this line to be one of the most dangerous alternatives that White has on the master level, but below 2000 I think you should have no stress at all facing this. It's like the master players who are using this are pretty much threatening us with a brand new Revolver, while the lower rated players are just trying to shoot us with a banana. Often they just drop it on the floor and even step on it while trying to get closer to us!} 
3. dxe4 {For the sake of simplicity we are going to stay away from the big alternative 3...Bg4 because why not transpose into the Tartakower if you can?} 
4. Nxe4
4. Nf6
5. Qe2 {This is White's only ambitious move and I would generally expect it to be played by people above 2000.5.Ng3This is the most common way for White to avoid the Tartakower transposition. I generally expect you to face it about 25%!5...g6∞This move is just a pain to deal with for the 5.Ng3 players!5.Nxf6+From my experience this is the most common move for lower rated games which just saves us a ton of time, not stressing about the 'Two Knights'.5...exf66.Bc4This is the only move to deviate from the standard path.6...Bd67.Qe2+!?This tricky move order is saying that we can no longer block the check in a convenient way by playing ...Be6, so Black needs to make a small concession.7...Be7∞Make sure to stay away from 7... Qe7 because the endgames are just risk free pressure for White. Why would you enter a battle where we can only draw at best?} 
5. Nxe4
6. Qxe4
6. Be6 {This has become the mainline recently. Black has a hidden trick to meet 7.d4 with 7...Bd5! and then ...Bxf3 which is either going to win the d4-pawn or White will accept the ruined structure after gxf3, which leads to a very comfortable game for Black.} 
7. b3 {This is the only threatening move.7.Bc4This move is pretty common online, but simply harmless.7...Bd5=There is of course, nothing wrong with trading the bishops, but Black can easily get a more pleasant position in case White decides to trade on our terms.} 
7. Nd7
8. Bb2
8. Nf6
9. Qe3 {This is White's most dangerous try and what gave me lots of headaches before settling for my recommendation.9.Qh4Bf5=We can play ... e6 on the next move and Black is pretty safe in the following lines.} 
9. Nd5 {After digging for days trying to come up with a human approach of holding, I decided that blackmailing White with a repetition is the best way to go.} 
10. Qd3 {10.Qd4Nf6=If we trade queens Black is very safe!10.Qe5Qc7=Inviting the endgames is the safest bet for us.} 
10. Nf6 {If White wants to avoid repetition, they need to play an inferior version.} 
