[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Two Knights Variation"]
[Black "5.Nxf6+ with 11.Bd2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. Nc3
2. d5
3. Nf3 {This is the starting position for the Two Knights Attack. I consider this together with the 'Advance Variation' to be the most dangerous lines that White has overall against the Caro-Kann, so we should definitely be well prepared.} 
3. dxe4 {I consider this move to be the most sensible choice for our repertoire because most players below 2000 will simply transpose into the Tartakower. Let's look at the alternatives:A) Black has the option of playing3...Bg4, which in theory is the most solid move, but it definitely requires a lot of knowledge and a deep understanding to avoid suffering without the bishop pair.B)3...Nf6used to be a thing in the past, but nowadays has massively dropped out of fashion (personally I think the risk/reward ratio is just not worth it anymore).C) Last but not least, if you are feeling 'cheeky' enough, the sideline starting with3...a6could lead to a fun game. Nevertheless I think the Tartakower transposition is by far the easiest line to play and clearly the most rewarding!} 
4. Nxe4
4. Nf6 {Inviting White to go for5.Nxf6+which leads to very familiar territory for us.} 
5. Nxf6+ {This is going to be the main choice for players below 2000, and generally just trnasposes to the normal lines (starting after1.e4c62.d4d53.Nc3or3.Nd2). Here we'll be mainly focusing on5.Nxf6+exf66.Bc4which is the only way to deviate from what we've covered in the 'Classical Variation'.} 
5. exf6
6. Bc4 {This is a tricky move order that can take a lot of newer players by surprise. The point is to follow it up with Qe2+ and then we don't have the usual way of blocking the check (...Be6) at our disposal.} 
6. Bd6
7. Qe2+ {We have arrived at the critical position for this sneaky little move order. Black has a choice between the somewhat ugly retreating move7...Be7or allowing the endgame after7...Qe7.} 
7. Be7 {I think this is the way to go for most players. The bishop will not stay forever on e7 (we are going back to d6 right after we castle), and we manage to avoid the relatively dull endgame.According to the computer, and as shown recently at the top level, there is nothing wrong with7...Qe7objectively speaking, but in my opinon I think this is not the true spirit of the Tartakower Variation. I just don't see why we should allow an endgame where White has 4 vs 3 pawns on the queenside (some people may call me out saying that 'this is why you are only an international master!'). Hey, perhaps they are right.} 
8. O-O
8. O-O
9. Re1
9. Bd6 {As promised, the bishop lands back on the d6 right after we castle.} 
10. d4
10. Na6 {This is always the key move to annihilate the c4-bishop in the Tartakower. The point is to play ...Nc7 followed by ...Be6 with a solid position.The automatic10...Bg4does not lead to disaster, but you need to be aware of11.Qe4!Bh512.Nh4!which could be annoying to deal with since12...Bg6??13.Nxg6hxg614.Qxg6!just wins a pawn for White.} 
11. Bd2 {This is another try by Ivanchuk, but Black got a more than comfortable game.11.Nh4This has been tried recently in a top level game.11...Nc712.Qd3Re813.Bd2Be614.Re2Qd7=We can continue with ...Bxc4 followed by ...Ne6 while Nf5 is always gonna be met by ...Bf8 with a solid position for Black.} 
11. Nc7
12. Qd3
12. a5
13. a4
13. Nd5
14. c3
14. Be6 {We can already stop here and claim that Black has an easy game, but I find the following moves quite instructive.} 
15. Bb3
15. Qd7
16. h3
16. Bf5 {Forcing White's queen onto a passive square.} 
17. Qf1
17. h5
18. Bd1
18. g5 {Black literally went full attacking mode and won in convincing fashion in the game between Ivanchuk-Duda, 2022.} 
