11. Bxa6 {This is the most critical option that White has, but it's not very common in my experience.11.Nh4This has been tried recently in a top level game.11...Nc712.Qd3Re813.Bd2Be614.Re2Qd7=We can continue with ...Bxc4 followed by ...Ne6, while Nf5 is always met by ...Bf8 with a solid position for Black.} 
11. bxa6 {It's difficult to predict what White can do now, but I will just add the most critical ideas that you need to be aware of.} 
12. Bd2 {12.b3This is the more human approach, but Black is definitely doing okay.12...a513.Bb2a4!This is very powerful because White will not be able to keep the extra pawn for long in case they decide to accept the bait.14.Nd2a315.Bc3a5∞We've managed to create a mess in White's queenside, which gives us a very reasonable position with the bishop pair.} 
12. a5 {We generally start with this move (gaining space on the queenside), while also preparing to develop the light squared bishop without losing the a6-pawn.} 
13. c4
