2. d5
3. Nf3 {This is the starting position for the Two Knights Attack. I consider this together with the 'Advance Variation' to be the most dangerous lines that White has overall against the Caro-Kann, so we should definitely be well prepared.} 
3. dxe4 {I consider this move to be the most sensible choice for our repertoire because most players below 2000 will simply transpose into the Tartakower. Let's look at the alternatives:A) Black has the option of playing3...Bg4, which in theory is the most solid move, but it definitely requires a lot of knowledge and a deep understanding to avoid suffering without the bishop pair.B)3...Nf6used to be a thing in the past, but nowadays has massively dropped out of fashion (personally I think the risk/reward ratio is just not worth it anymore).C) Last but not least, if you are feeling 'cheeky' enough, the sideline starting with3...a6could lead to a fun game. Nevertheless I think the Tartakower transposition is by far the easiest line to play and clearly the most rewarding!} 
4. Nxe4
4. Nf6 {Inviting White to go for5.Nxf6+which leads to very familiar territory for us.} 
5. Qe2 {This weird looking move is White's only try for an advantage. If you are below 1800 online rating, I would typically expect this 1 out of 10 games (so almost never), but once you cross 2000 you can expect to face this more and more.} 
5. Nxe4 {Since exchanges are generally fine in the Caro-Kann, I see no reason why to avoid this move.If you are looking for interesting alternatives, be my guest and have a look on moves such as5...Na6!?,5...Be6and5...Bf5. In my repertoire we are going to stick with what I believe to be the simplest and simultaneously the best, objectively speaking.} 
6. Qxe4
6. Be6 {There are only around 200 games with this variation which only really started getting played in 2019 (which is absolutely nuts, considering how saturated opening theory is in general). The point is to meet the most natural move7.d4with7...Bd5!followed by ...Bxf3 and then White will either have to allow the ruined structure or sacrifice the d4-pawn (for not a lot of compensation).There is nothing wrong with Sielecki's6...Nd7(in fact I've even played it myself), but I consider the amount of theory required to be a bit overwhelming for the average player.Another popular move is6...Qa5(recommended by GothamChess in his course), but I find the variations starting with7.Qf4very tricky to deal with. Especially considering the fact that we need to enter the positions arising after6...Qa57.Qf4!Qf58.Qe3Qxc2to get a reasonable shot at equality, but one wrong step could easily lose us the game.} 
7. c4 {This move is quite common both for OTB and online chess. The point is to stop Black from playing ...Bd5!} 
7. g6 {This move becomes quite tempting specifically after White has played 7.c4 because the bishop will be really active on the long diagonal. Normally the fianchetto could become a bit passive in case White plays c3, but luckily for you, I am here to give away the Grandmaster secret which says 'pawns do not move backwards'.} 
8. d4 {8.Qe5may look a bit scary in the first place, but it could actually get White in trouble!8...Rg8Sidestepping White's threat while preparing ...Bg7 on the next move.9.d4Bg4∞This very precise move can easily be missed if you stick with the automatic9...Bg7(which is not terrible, but just not as good). The point of9...Bg4is that we are about to play ...Bxf3 next no matter what, followed by ...Bg7 with a slightly better position for Black already.} 
8. Bg7
9. Be2
9. b5 {This is not the only move to get a reasonable position, but after doing a lot of digging, this is by far the most fun line to play.} 
10. cxb5 {10.b3bxc411.bxc4Bf512.Qh4c5⇆Completely destroys White's center.} 
10. Bd5
11. Qh4
11. cxb5
12. Bxb5+
12. Nc6
13. O-O
13. O-O {Threatening ...Bxf3 followed by ...Nxd4!} 
14. Bxc6
14. Bxc6
15. Ne5
15. Bb7
16. Be3
16. Qd5 {With full compensation for the pawn thanks to the bishop pair.} 
