7. Be2 {This is sometimes played by stronger players, but super rare.7.c3This is another rare move for White, but the point is to have the d4-pawn defended to avoid the double pawns which is common for the 7.d4 variation.7...Nd78.d4Bd5I like starting with this move because it makes Qh4 lines less appealing for White because of ...Bxf3!9.Qe39.Qf4g610.Qg3Bg711.Be2O-O12.O-ORe8=We are ready to push ...e5 on the next move, which equalizes fully.9...g6I prefer this approach against the early c3, because it seems that White is having a hard time stopping the e5-break later on.10.Bd3Bg711.O-OO-O =I don't see how White is going to stop ideas such as ...Bxf3 followed by ...e5 where Black is super comfortable.} 
7. Nd7
8. d4 {8.O-ONf69.Qh4Bf5Preparing to finish development with ...e6-Be7!10.c3e611.d4Be712.Bg5O-O13.Ne5h6Forcing White to do something.It's important to notice that14.Bxh6Ng4!is completely crushing!14.Bxf6Bxf615.Qg3Rc8=We are ready to break with ...c5 next and Black is completely fine.} 
8. Nf6
9. Qd3
9. Bg4 {At this point9...g6is also reasonable, but I think this approach is a bit simpler.} 
10. h3
10. Bh5
11. O-O
11. e6 {Preparing to play ...Be7 and finish development.} 
12. c4
12. Be7
13. Be3
13. O-O
14. Rfd1
14. Qc7 {We can continue with ...Rfd8 followed by ...c5 with a balanced game.} 
