7. Nd7 {Preparing to play ...Nf6 and then we decide depending on where White goes with the queen.} 
8. Bb2
8. Nf6 {At this point White could go for any queen move, but generally they play either9.Qh4or9.Qe3. The alternatives will be mentioned in the 'informational' file.} 
9. Qe3 {This move is very common both OTB and online.} 
9. Nd5 {As weird as this may look, I think it is definitely safer than the standard9...Bf510.Nd4which requries a lot of move by move stuff just to survive.The main point of9...Nd5is to meet10.Qe4with10...Nf6and Black is happy to repeat the position.} 
10. Qd3
10. Nf6 {We are happy to exchange queens or repeat the position in case of11.Qe3Nd5!} 
11. Nd4
11. Bd7
12. O-O-O
12. g6 {Going for the fianchetto is the safest option.} 
13. Re1
13. Bg7
14. f4
14. O-O
15. Nf3
15. a5 {We have managed to castle without allowing any nonsense. Black is ready to break on the queenside with ...a4 (if allowed). Please keep in mind that15.a4b5!gives us a good position.} 
