[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Panov Attack"]
[Black "Panov: Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4 {2.c4This is the 'Pseudo-Panov' variation, or the line that gives many new Caro players nightmares after they decided to hop onto the Caro-Kann train.2...d53.exd5cxd54.cxd5Nf6!Preparing to take back on d5 with the knight! This is the first key idea to remember because 4...Qxd5 5.Nc3 allows White to gain a tempo for no particular reason.5.Qa4+This is the most evil way of playing the Panov as White. It's truly a life-hack to get easy positions where Black has so many ways to go wrong.5.Nc3This move is leading to the normal IQP positions, but basically saying that White is simply happy for playing a 'Panov-like position' while avoiding the super dry endgame that Black can force in the traditional line after 1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.exd5 cxd5 4.c4 Nf6 5.Nc3 Nc6 6.Nf3 Bg4 and we all know how that goes...5...Nxd56.Nf3Nc67.Bb5g6∞Black is typically getting a very solid position using the fianchetto.5...Nbd7∞This is the key move to remember whenever White goes for the early checks (5.Qa4+/5.Bb5+). Black will continue with moves such as ...g6-Bg7 followed by short castle and the queenside is generally developed by playing .. .a6-b5/b6 with ...Bb7 and only later we are winning back the d5-pawn with a solid position.} 
2. d5
3. exd5
3. cxd5
4. c4 {Here we have the starting position for the 'Panov Attack'. In the grand scheme of things, this variation is quite rare, but it definitely catches a lot of people off guard whenever it happens. It's usually like the controller who just walks by when you are using the public transport without a ticket... You may get away sometimes, but it's always a twisted experience!} 
4. Nf6
5. Nc3
5. e6 {My favorite sauce for taking down this evil opening. We never really want to block our light-squared bishop, but against c4 it really makes sense. (Just look at the final position to understand why.)} 
6. Nf3
6. Be7
7. Bd3 {This is the most common move for lower rated players, just developing casually and preparing short castle.7.cxd5This is the more professional approach for White, avoiding the 'tempo steal'. Black can recapture either way and be fine though!7...exd5!?I consider this move to be really underrated. If White goes for the ambitious 8.Bb5+ & 9.Ne5, they can easily get caught in our prep! The only drawback of this is that if White plays 'safe', it will be pretty difficult to win. So for this reason I will also give 7...Nxd5 in the course as an alternative trainable, in case you need a more imbalanced position.8.Bb5+Nc69.Ne5O-O !This pawn sacrifice is really sexy! If Black can get away just like that, we never pay for a ticket again.10.Nxc6bxc611.Bxc611...Rb812.O-OBd6=∞Creating a direct threat of ...Bxh2+ followed by ...Qd6+ (winning back the piece) with a good position. Black has tremendous pressure against White's king in the following fascinating variations that can appear, so make sure to check out the trainables for more.7.c5This move opens the portal to a new dimension! Black needs to be careful not to get overwhelmed by the queenside play connected with b4-a4-b5 and simply marching down the pawns like it's parade day.7...O-O8.b4Ne4⇆This is the key idea to get counterplay, otherwise Black's position will be pretty sad. So make sure to create counterplay in the center!} 
7. dxc4 {Stealing a tempo! This is a very important idea to use whenever you are considering to enter the isolated pawn positions. You want to make sure that White has to make some extra effort to recapture the pawn, otherwise they will be getting a head start in this race.} 
8. Bxc4
8. O-O
9. O-O
9. Nc6 {Keeping pressure on the d4-pawn. This is way better than the passive9...Nbd7.} 
10. Re1
10. b6
11. Bg5
11. Bb7 {We can continue with ...Rc8 followed by ...Nb4-Nd5 ideas where Black has an easy position to play with no bad pieces. Here you get to understand why ...e6 is not a disaster against c4, just look how powerful the bishop on b7 is! It is a true king on the long diagonal and White needs to be really careful.} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Panov Attack"]
[Black "4.c4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e6 6.Nf3 Be7 with 7.Bd3 & 11.d5"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d4
2. d5
3. exd5
3. cxd5
4. c4 {This is the traditional way of playing the Panov Attack. White's position is pretty easy to play, but besides that there are not too many positive aspects! Black has many ways to equalise + some newer lines in order to try and outplay White.However, in this repertoire we will be going over what I find to be the easiest set-up to play where you basically only need to know where our pieces belong. After that, you should have a completely fine position, which you can use to try and play for a win later on in the game.} 
4. Nf6
5. Nc3
5. e6 {This move may seem a bit ugly at first, but it is actually not that bad and it will keep us pretty safe.The main idea that is important to understand is simply that chess is a reactive game! We can compare it with tennis, because in both games you need to react to what your opponent does. In this case because they have played c4, which completely justifies the ...e6 move, because it makes Black's center feel pretty solid.One key detail that lower rated players often fail to understand is that our light-squared bishop will not be blocked for the rest of the game, but we have ideas to go ...dxc4 (once White develops the light-squared bishop) followed by ...b6-Bb7, occupying the monster diagonal.While there is nothing wrong with entering the variation arising after5...Nc66.Nf3Bg4, I personally simply dislike having to learn 20 moves of theory just to enter a drawish endgame (mess up one move and you can easily get a losing position).Another decent option is5...g6, but once again I feel like we are over-complicating things with this approach.Before we move on there is one last important detail: the move order does matter! Playing5...Nc6?!is a mistake from our point of view, because after6.Nf3e67.c5!White is slightly better. The right way of entering these ...e6 lines is5...e6!, which I will explain later.} 
6. Nf3 {This is the most popular move. White does not really have many alternatives besides6.c5(other moves will most likely transpose).} 
6. Be7 {Once again, in my opinion this is the simplest move.There is nothing wrong with6...Bb4from a theoretical perspective, but giving up the bishop pair is not a very obvious decision and it can easily get us in trouble. Intellectuals solve problems, while geniuses prevent them. You get the point!} 
7. Bd3 {This is the second most common move, or if you think about the fact that7.Be2leads to the same thing ➼ it is actually the most common variation overall!} 
7. dxc4 {Entering the IQP position in an ideal way (waiting for White to lose a tempo first by developing their light-squared bishop).} 
8. Bxc4
8. O-O
9. O-O
9. Nc6 {This is the best square for the knight because it puts pressure on the d4-pawn while preparing future maneuvers such as ...Nb4-Nd5 or ...Na5-Nc4 (after ...b6-Bb7-Rc8).} 
10. Re1
10. b6 {This is the key move to solve the issue of our light-squared bishop. From b7, the bishop will have no rival on the long diagonal!} 
11. d5 {This is a common try for White ➼ meant to achieve a symmetrical position where White is slightly better. However, little do they know what's coming!} 
11. Na5 {This move changes the winrate dramatically in Black's favor(even though the computer thinks White gets enough compensation for the pawn).} 
12. Bd3
12. exd5
13. Bg5
13. h6
14. Bh4
14. Bb7 {The engine evaluates this position as equal, but as Jan Gustafsson likes to say, 'A pawn is a pawn!'. According to the statistics Black is performing really well in online games after the move 11...Na5!} 
