11. Bg5 {This is the most common developing move for White. Let's also look at some alternatives:A)11.Ne5This is recommended by the computer, but I don't really expect you to see it very often.11...Bb7=. I went over the complicated lines arising after11...Nxd412.Be3Nf513.Qf3and despite the fact that Leela is able to work her way out, I prefer the simpler line (in case the evaluation doesn't change).B)11.a3This is a useful move for White, but it doesn't change much about the pawn structure.11...Bb712.Be3I picked this move because 12. Bg5 most likely transposes.12...Rc813.Ba2Na5=Since ...Nb4-Nbd5 is no longer available after White has pushed a3, we can instead rely on ...Na5-Nc4 with good counterplay on the queenside.} 
11. Bb7
12. Rc1
12. Rc8 {What I really love about this variation is the fact that you can simply remember the final position and this will make it incredibly easy to figure out how to play the opening, in case you have a hard time memorizing variations. Focus on what the pawn structure looks like and where each piece belongs, and my friends, you have the reciepe for succes!From now on, we can continue with a typical maneuver such as ...Nb4-Nbd5 with a very solid position. The general strategy is to exchange pieces, and as long as White does not get any attack against our king ➼ Black is slightly better in the endgames by default (thanks to the better pawn structure).} 
