3. exd5
3. cxd5
4. c4 {This is the traditional way of playing the Panov Attack. White's position is pretty easy to play, but besides that there are not too many positive aspects! Black has many ways to equalise + some newer lines in order to try and outplay White.However, in this repertoire we will be going over what I find to be the easiest set-up to play where you basically only need to know where our pieces belong. After that, you should have a completely fine position, which you can use to try and play for a win later on in the game.} 
4. Nf6
5. Nc3
5. e6 {This move may seem a bit ugly at first, but it is actually not that bad and it will keep us pretty safe.The main idea that is important to understand is simply that chess is a reactive game! We can compare it with tennis, because in both games you need to react to what your opponent does. In this case because they have played c4, which completely justifies the ...e6 move, because it makes Black's center feel pretty solid.One key detail that lower rated players often fail to understand is that our light-squared bishop will not be blocked for the rest of the game, but we have ideas to go ...dxc4 (once White develops the light-squared bishop) followed by ...b6-Bb7, occupying the monster diagonal.While there is nothing wrong with entering the variation arising after5...Nc66.Nf3Bg4, I personally simply dislike having to learn 20 moves of theory just to enter a drawish endgame (mess up one move and you can easily get a losing position).Another decent option is5...g6, but once again I feel like we are over-complicating things with this approach.Before we move on there is one last important detail: the move order does matter! Playing5...Nc6?!is a mistake from our point of view, because after6.Nf3e67.c5!White is slightly better. The right way of entering these ...e6 lines is5...e6!, which I will explain later.} 
6. Nf3 {This is the most popular move. White does not really have many alternatives besides6.c5(other moves will most likely transpose).} 
6. Be7 {Once again, in my opinion this is the simplest move.There is nothing wrong with6...Bb4from a theoretical perspective, but giving up the bishop pair is not a very obvious decision and it can easily get us in trouble. Intellectuals solve problems, while geniuses prevent them. You get the point!} 
7. cxd5 {This is the most common move across all rating ranges.} 
7. Nxd5 {This is a viable option if you want to keep the position a bit more unbalanced. Against weaker players we can squeeze the isolated pawn in a long fight, while against stronger players we might get under a bit of attack (but with proper knowledge Black should be holding according to Leela).} 
8. Bd3 {This is by far the main continuation.8.Nxd5This may be the choice of weaker players.8...Qxd59.Be2O-O10.O-ONc611.Be3b6Going for the standard fianchetto since ...Bd7 is quite passive.12.Rc1Bb713.Bc4Qd614.Qe2Bf615.Rfd1Ne7=WIth a balanced position so far, but definitely with good chances to outplay our opponent later on.} 
8. O-O
9. O-O
9. Nc6
10. Re1
10. Bf6 {Creating a positional threat of ...Ndb4!} 
11. Be4 {This is pretty much the only dangerous line that we need to be aware of. White could go for other moves too, but I don't want to go too crazy with the details, since this is not the main goal for our repertoire.11.Ne4Bxd4!12.Nxd4Nxd4=White should have enough compensation for the pawn with best play, but Black is definitely ok.} 
11. Nce7 {Reinforcing the d5-knight while preparing ...Bd7-Bc6 ideas.} 
12. Qd3
12. h6 {This is quite important to remember. The alternatives are just worse!} 
13. Ne5
13. Bd7
14. Qg3
14. Bc6 {Ignoring White's threat of Bxh6! This is really important because the other lines lead to suffering for Black.} 
15. Nxc6 {15.Bxh6?!Falling for the temptation could easily get White in trouble!15...Nxc316.Nxc6Nxe4!This intermezzo is easy to miss.17.Nxe7+Kh7!The real key move of this line!18.Rxe4gxh6⩱White needs to find19.Rxe6!!in order not to be much worse now.15.Ng4This may seem dangerous at first, but I think Black has a pretty nice way of dealing with this.15...h5!According to the computer 15...Ng6 also holds, but it's way more complicated to play for Black.16.Nxf6+Nxf617.Bh6Ng4!Offense is the best defense!18.Bg5f619.Bf4Bxe420.Rxe4Nf5=With a balanced position. Keep in mind that White's position can easily become pretty risky after the tempting21.Qh3Qb6!22.Qxh5Nxf2!and Black gets very good counterplay.} 
15. bxc6 {It's important to roecapture this way in order to keep the idea of ...Nf5! available (an important concept for this line).} 
16. Bxh6
16. Qb8 {I really like this move because it tries to force a queen trade while applying pressure on the b2-pawn.} 
17. Qh3 {White needs to keep queens on in order to show any ambition.} 
17. Nf5 {The key defensive move!} 
18. Bxf5
18. exf5
19. Nxd5
19. cxd5
20. Qxf5
20. Bxd4
21. Be3
21. Bxe3
22. Rxe3
22. Qxb2 {So far this was best play for both sides, leading to a pretty comfortable draw for Black. Some of you may be wondering 'How is this playing for a win?!' The main idea is that White had plenty of ways to go wrong along the way. Against perfect play it will generally be difficult to win (especially as Black), but personally I wouldn't risk more than this.} 
