[White "6) Panov Attack"]
[Black "2.c4 d5 3.exd5 cxd5 4.cxd5 Nf6 with 5.Qa4+ & 12.Be3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. c4 {The starting position of the 'Pseudo Panov' variation. This is an interesting line for White because it gives them ideas to play annoying moves such as5.Qa4+or just reach the normal IQP positions with5.Nc3(while avoiding the ...Bg4 endgames). From White's perspective, this move is definitely interesting, but as long as you know the main little details, Black should get at least an equal position.} 
2. d5
3. exd5 {3.cxd5cxd54.e5This line does not make a whole lot of sense, but it could get played against you specifically in online chess.4...Qa5!?This weird move is actually the main counter to White's little set-up. The point is to stop them from pushing d4 with ease while waiting to meet Nf3 with ...Bg4, leading to similar positions to what we've seen in the 'Advance Variation' chapter.5.Nf3Nc66.Nc3Bg4=We can continue with the typical development for the 'Advance Variation' by going ...e6-Nge7-Nf5 followed by ...Be7 and ...O-O (while always meeting h3 with ...Bxf3).} 
3. cxd5
4. cxd5
4. Nf6 {This is the first move important to remember. You have no idea how many beginners go for the 'tempting'4...Qxd5which is just worse because it allows5.Nc3and White develops by gaining a tempo.} 
5. Qa4+ {I consider this to be the most interesting try for White. (It's super rare below 2000!)} 
5. Nbd7 {The most precise reply! Just remember to block with the knight against both5.Bb5+and5.Qa4+.5...Bd7This variation is a bit harder to play. Now6.Qb3is a little annoying, but still playable for Black with precise play.} 
6. Nc3
6. g6 {This is the standard way to develop with White's d5-pawn. We can just play around it for a while and later on we should be able to regain the pawn with a good position.} 
7. Bc4
7. Bg7
8. d3
8. O-O
9. Nf3
9. a6 {Creating a big threat of ...b5!} 
10. Qa3 {Setting up a small trap because10...b5allows11.Bxb5!10.O-O ??would be a terrible blunder.10...b5!11.Bxb5Nb6-+Protecting the a8-rook so we can collect the b5-bishop on the very next move.} 
10. b6 {Simply aiming to finish development.} 
11. O-O
11. Bb7
12. Be3 {This move is pretty rare, but not easy to counter if unprepared.} 
12. b5
13. Bb3
13. Nb6 {Sacrificing another pawn!} 
14. Bxb6
14. Qxb6
15. Qxe7
15. a5 {Creating a big threat of ...Rae8 which would win material.} 
16. Qe3 {This is the only move that was tried by White in OTB chess so far.} 
16. Qxe3
17. fxe3
17. a4
18. Bd1
18. Ng4 {Black has a direct threat of ...Nxe3, and is also preparing to break the queenside with ...a3!? Black was more than comfortable and went on to win the game between Wang-Wei, China 2017.} 
