3. f3 {This is the starting position for the 'Fantasy Variation'. The name sort of speaks for itself, and it's known for giving nightmares to the average lower rated player.I consider this opening to be very interesting for White, but generally it is dangerous only in the hands of skilled players, since it requires quite a bit of move by move knowledge. From my experience with Black, players below 1800 tend to collapse pretty quickly if you play it properly.} 
3. e5 {Black has a variety of standard ways to get a very reasonable position, but they do require a decent amount of theory. Two perfectly playable alternatives are3...dxe44.fxe4e55.Nf3Bg46.c3Nd7and3...Qb64.Nc3dxe45.fxe4e5!.The main reason for sticking with the somewhat 'wild'3...e5!?is that you can easily get a quick win, and it makes even higher rated players feel pretty uncomfortable. The line is a bit inferior compared to the other alternatives mentioned, but I think the risk-reward ratio is super profitable especially below 2000 online rating.} 
4. exd5 {This is pretty common in lower rated games.} 
4. Qh4+ {While Black has many ways of getting a reasonable position, I think going for the endgame is the easiest.} 
5. g3
5. Qxd4
6. Qxd4
6. exd4
7. dxc6 {7.Ne2d3!This pawn sacrifice makes it difficult for White to finish development.8.cxd3Nf69.dxc6Nxc6=∞We can continue with ...Bf5-Bc5 followed by ...O-O (while constantly keeping an eye on ...Nb4 ideas).} 
7. Nxc6
8. Bb5
8. Bf5 {Black is already slightly better because we have annoying pressure on the c2-square.} 
