3. e5 {Black has a variety of standard ways to get a very reasonable position, but they do require a decent amount of theory. Two perfectly playable alternatives are3...dxe44.fxe4e55.Nf3Bg46.c3Nd7and3...Qb64.Nc3dxe45.fxe4e5!.The main reason for sticking with the somewhat 'wild'3...e5!?is that you can easily get a quick win, and it makes even higher rated players feel pretty uncomfortable. The line is a bit inferior compared to the other alternatives mentioned, but I think the risk-reward ratio is super profitable especially below 2000 online rating.} 
4. Nc3 {This is the second most common move after 4. dxe5.} 
4. dxe4 {Creating a threat of ...Qxd4!} 
5. dxe5
5. Qxd1+
6. Nxd1
6. Nd7
7. f4
7. f6
8. exf6 {8.e6may seem dangerous, but White is unable to hold on to this pawn:8...Nc59.f5g6!10.g4h5∓White's position is collapsing because11.h3hxg4!wins for Black because the h1-rook remains unprotected.} 
8. Ngxf6 {We can continue with ...Nb6-Be6-Bc5 followed by ...O-O with a slightly better endgame.} 
