3. f3 {This is the starting position for the 'Fantasy Variation'. The name sort of speaks for itself, and it's known for giving nightmares to the average lower rated player.I consider this opening to be very interesting for White, but generally it is dangerous only in the hands of skilled players, since it requires quite a bit of move by move knowledge. From my experience with Black, players below 1800 tend to collapse pretty quickly if you play it properly.} 
3. e5 {Black has a variety of standard ways to get a very reasonable position, but they do require a decent amount of theory. Two perfectly playable alternatives are3...dxe44.fxe4e55.Nf3Bg46.c3Nd7and3...Qb64.Nc3dxe45.fxe4e5!.The main reason for sticking with the somewhat 'wild'3...e5!?is that you can easily get a quick win, and it makes even higher rated players feel pretty uncomfortable. The line is a bit inferior compared to the other alternatives mentioned, but I think the risk-reward ratio is super profitable especially below 2000 online rating.} 
4. dxe5 {This is by far the main move and what I expect you to face in about 2 out of 3 games.} 
4. Bc5 {Immediately targeting the vulnerable diagonal. With this variation we are trying to highlight the main drawback of the move 3.f3. Now, from my experience and according to the stats, below 2000 online rating, you are going to face both5.Nc3and5.exd5around 50/50. If you are planning to use this line for higher rated games, you should be expecting5.Nc3more often.} 
5. Nc3 {This is White's only move to fight for an advantage. The point is to meet5...Qb6with6.Na4!and White is getting a small edge with precise play!} 
5. Ne7 {I consider this to be the best practical try according to the stats. If you go for5...Qb6White is usually going to answer6.Na4, which can be somewhat difficult to deal with.After5...Ne7, it's pretty hard to predict what our opponent is going to play, so I will show all the decent options that White has.} 
6. f4 {This move seems to be super rare, but the computer quite likes it.} 
6. Qb6
7. Nf3
7. Bf2+
8. Ke2 {Creating a big threat of Na4 when the f2-bishop remains undefended.} 
8. a5 {This is important so we can meet9.Na4with9...Qa7!} 
9. Qd3 {Preparing to play Be3.} 
9. Na6 {Creating a pretty annoying threat of going ...Nc5!} 
10. Be3
10. Bxe3
11. Qxe3
11. Nc5 {The computer does not like11...Qxb212.Rb1Qxc2+13.Ke1and Black does not have a way to follow up the attack.} 
12. Rd1
12. dxe4
13. Nxe4
13. Qb5+
14. Kf2
14. Nxe4+
15. Qxe4
15. Qxb2 {With a small edge for White with precise play according to the computer, but I feel like Black's position should be pretty safe after ...Qb6+ followed by ...O-O!} 
