[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 2.Nf3 d5 3.d3 and 2.d3"]
[Black "d3 lines: Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. d3 {In this chapter we will focus on the somewhat 'odd' d3-lines. The variations will be a bit different to what you are normally used to, because going ... dxe4 in a lot of positions is not great for us when White can recapture on e4 with the pawn.} 
2. d5
3. Nf3 {Introduced by Jorden Van Foreest in 2019, this line has since then become incredibly popular at the top level. This move clearly doesn't refute the Caro-Kann, but mainly seeks for fresh positions to get a game.3.Nd2This is the most common move that I expect you to see amongst club level games. White goes for an 'easy' set-up, preparing g3-Bg2-Ngf3 followed by O-O. Widely known as the 'King's Indian Attack', this opening always confused me because there is no attack!3...g6This is the bread and butter for our repertoire when it comes to dealing with d3 lines.4.Ngf3Bg75.g3Nh6!?This move is surprisingly strong.6.Bg2O-O7.O-Oe5=Black is able to take control over the center thanks to the knight on the edge. We are going to continue with ... f6-Nf7 followed by ...a5-Na6-Nc7-Be6 and ultimately break with ...f5!} 
3. g6 {Staying true to the spirit of our repertoire and going ...g6 against d3! I think this is definitely more practical than trying to understand the upcoming endgames after 3...dxe4! At the end of the day, a stronger player is happy to grind you down from an equal (and risk free) position, the way I see chess nowadays.} 
4. e5 {This is White's only ambitious attempt.4.Be2The reversed Philidor set-up is quite harmless.4...Bg75.O-Oe56.c3Ne77.Re1O-O8.Bf1Re8=We are ready to continue with ... c5-Nbc6 while ...h6 is always a useful move in this structure because it allows us to play ...Be6 without having to worry about Ng5 ideas.} 
4. Bg4 {Careful with the move order! It's important not to rush with the 'natural'4...Bg7because it's not clear yet that this will be the ideal square for the bishop after White has pushed e5 on the previous move.} 
5. d4 {This is by far the most common move for White.5.Nbd2This idea is very logical, preparing to play h3 and then recapture on f3 with the knight. Despite being one of the best tries for White objectively speaking, this is definitely pretty rare.5...c5⇆After this important move White is going to have a hard time protecting the e5-pawn.} 
5. c5 {Immediately hitting the center and preparing to play ...Nc6! This variation really resembles the main idea from our 'Advance Variation', which makes the whole repertoire mix together pretty nicely.} 
6. c3
6. Nc6 {Creating a positional threat of ...Bxf3! After this move White has a pretty wide choice.} 
7. Be2 {This move strikes me as the most natural, simply breaking the pin.7.Bb5This is another way to defend the d4-pawn.7...Bxf38.Bxc6+bxc69.Qxf3e610.O-Oh5=We are going to play ...Nh6-Nf5 with a balanced position.7.Nbd2This move can be pretty tricky, so it's important to remember the following key combo!7...cxd48.cxd4Qa5⇆White has a hard time dealing with all these pins.} 
7. Bxf3
8. Bxf3
8. e6 {We are going to play ...Nge7-Nf5 with pressure on d4.} 
