[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 2.Nf3 d5 3.d3 and 2.d3"]
[Black "4.e5 Bg4 with 5.h3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. Nf3
2. d5
3. d3 {This variation was introduced quite recently (in 2016) by the incredibly talented and very creative Grandmaster Jorden van Foreest. It is definitely a very interesting variation, which seeks to obtain fresh positions where you can try to catch your opponent off guard, since the mainlines have been analyzed to death, and Black has already proved to be quite comfortable in all the mainlines. I would really expect to face this line from time to time if you are above 2200 online, but below that I think you will more or less never get to face it.} 
3. g6 {This move is very solid and pretty consistent at the top level recently. The main thing that I love about it is that it mixes really nicely with our repertoire, because (as you'll see more often in this chapter) we have this theme to meet d3-lines by going for a ...g6 fianchetto.I was debating myself whether to enter the endgame or go for the interesting3...Qc7, but after doing a lot of analysis I came to the following conclusions:•3...dxe44.dxe4Qxd1+5.Kxd1is not really that much about move by move theory, but mainly about your understanding of endgames in general (which is difficult for me to help you with in an opening course).•3...Qc74.exd5cxd55.c4!?leads to some very strange positions that are super dangerous - just one wrong step and it could be enough to lose (which is definitely not a very practical approach against a rare line).•3...Bg44.h3Bh55.Qe2e66.g4Bg67.h4could be playable for Black, but it's a bit too dangerous for my taste.} 
4. e5 {This is by far the most common move and the only critical test for Black. The point is to restrict our dark-squared bishop, but things are not that simple!} 
4. Bg4 {After analysing a lot both4...Bg7and4...c5I came to the conclusion that they are both playable with proper knowledge, but the amount of theory was getting a bit out of hand while some lines could definitely become pretty unusual. I feel like going for4...Bg4is way more 'set-up based', which makes it quite easy to play without having to rely much on the move by move stuff.} 
5. h3 {This natural move could easily get White in trouble.} 
5. Bxf3
6. Qxf3
6. c5 {Preparing to play ...Nc6 on the next move (putting pressure on the e5-pawn). White could easily lose control over the e5-square if they are not careful.} 
7. Qe2 {This is a safe move because it prepares to push f4 (making sure that the e5-pawn is well-defended).} 
7. Nc6
8. c3
8. Bg7
9. f4
9. e6
10. Nd2
10. Nge7
11. Nf3
11. Nf5 {Creating a huge threat of ...Ng3!} 
12. Qf2
12. h5 {We can improve our position with ideas such as ...Bf8-Be7 next, while13.Qxc5can be met by13...d4!with very good compensation for Black.} 
