[Black "4.e5 Bg4 5.d4 c5 6.c3 Nc6 with 7.Nbd2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
1. c6
2. Nf3
2. d5
3. d3 {This variation was introduced quite recently (in 2016) by the incredibly talented and very creative Grandmaster Jorden van Foreest. It is definitely a very interesting variation, which seeks to obtain fresh positions where you can try to catch your opponent off guard, since the mainlines have been analyzed to death, and Black has already proved to be quite comfortable in all the mainlines. I would really expect to face this line from time to time if you are above 2200 online, but below that I think you will more or less never get to face it.} 
3. g6 {This move is very solid and pretty consistent at the top level recently. The main thing that I love about it is that it mixes really nicely with our repertoire, because (as you'll see more often in this chapter) we have this theme to meet d3-lines by going for a ...g6 fianchetto.I was debating myself whether to enter the endgame or go for the interesting3...Qc7, but after doing a lot of analysis I came to the following conclusions:•3...dxe44.dxe4Qxd1+5.Kxd1is not really that much about move by move theory, but mainly about your understanding of endgames in general (which is difficult for me to help you with in an opening course).•3...Qc74.exd5cxd55.c4!?leads to some very strange positions that are super dangerous - just one wrong step and it could be enough to lose (which is definitely not a very practical approach against a rare line).•3...Bg44.h3Bh55.Qe2e66.g4Bg67.h4could be playable for Black, but it's a bit too dangerous for my taste.} 
4. e5 {This is by far the most common move and the only critical test for Black. The point is to restrict our dark-squared bishop, but things are not that simple!} 
4. Bg4 {After analysing a lot both4...Bg7and4...c5I came to the conclusion that they are both playable with proper knowledge, but the amount of theory was getting a bit out of hand while some lines could definitely become pretty unusual. I feel like going for4...Bg4is way more 'set-up based', which makes it quite easy to play without having to rely much on the move by move stuff.} 
5. d4 {This is by far the most common move for White.} 
5. c5 {Undermining White's center and preparing to play ...Nc6, with positions that are similar to what we can normally get from the 'Advance Variation', except here we have this ...g6-move on the board (the strategy remains more or less the same though).} 
6. c3 {This is White's most natural move, simply preparing to recapture back with the pawn and keep a solid pawn center. Suddenly we are back into similar positions to what we have seen in the 'Advance Variation'.6.Be2This move can get White in trouble, because they are losing control over the center.6...Bxf37.Bxf3cxd48.Qxd4e6Protecting the d5-pawn.9.O-ONe710.Bg5Bg7=We can continue with ...O-O followed by ...Nbc6 with very annoying pressure on the e5-pawn.} 
6. Nc6
7. Nbd2 {This is an interesting try for White because with normal play, if they are in time to simply recapture back with the knight on f3 and then castle, White is just better without much counterplay.} 
7. cxd4
8. cxd4
8. Qa5 {This is the path leading to complete equality! White does not have an easy way to protect the d4-pawn because they are pinned everywhere.8...Bg7?!is something that you could play without any prior knowledge. While it is leads to an inferior position, it's still not a disaster by any means!9.h3Bxf310.Nxf3e611.Bd3Nge712.Be3O-O13.O-Of6!It's important to break with ...f6 in order to activate the dark-squared bishop.14.exf6Bxf615.Re1Bg7⩲White keeps a small edge because of the bishop pair + the somewhat vulnerable e6-pawn, but there is still definitely lot of work to do.} 
9. Qb3 {White needs to come up with this move in order to get a reasonable position.9.Be2This natural move  just loses a pawn.9...Bxf3!White is unable to recapture with the knight, which is the main point behind 8...Qa5!?10.Bxf3Nxd411.O-Oe612.Nb3Nxf3+13.Qxf3Qd8=White definitely has some compensation for the pawn, but it feels more like a blunder than a 'sacrifice'.} 
9. Qb4 {This is the most efficient way of protecting the b7-pawn.9...Bxf3??This may look quite tempting, trying to ruin White's pawn structure.10.Qxb7+-However, White is completely winning after this little intermezzo.} 
10. Bb5
10. e6 {Notice how effective the strategy of delaying the fianchetto really is! The dark-squared bishop can become really active on the queenside.} 
11. Qxb4
11. Bxb4
12. a3 {This is the most straightforward continuation, leading to a pretty forcing variation.12.Ke2is leads to slower play.12...Bxd2It's important to throw this move in, as otherwise the bishop might remain out of the game.13.Bxc6+bxc614.Bxd2Ne715.h3Bxf3+16.Kxf3Here we get to see the main point behind 12.Ke2! White is able to keep a healthy pawn structure.16...Nf517.Bc3Nh4+18.Kg3Nf5+19.Kh2h5=Stopping g4 and securing a solid position. We are going to play ...Kd7 and the game is quite balanced.} 
12. Bxf3
13. axb4
13. Bxg2
14. Bxc6+
14. bxc6
15. Rg1
15. Be4 {We have the extra pawn, but the position is roughly equal since White will most likely win it back.} 
