1. e4
1. c6
2. d3 {This variation is exactly like that weird uncle who visits occassionaly (while being semi-drunk) and is always asking how is your love life going. It is pretty unexpected and could be quite tricky to deal with, but don't worry because I think I came up with a good recipe!} 
2. d5
3. Nd2 {This is the classical way of playing the King's Indian Attack. Nowadays people have started playing the fancy3.Nf3quite often at the top level, but we should definitely not underestimate3.Nd2because White could easily get an edge by knowing the upcoming positions better. The move by move stuff is less important against this line, but we need to have a decent understanding of the main plans for the upcoming positions.} 
3. g6 {Once again, we are deviating from the most common path. As a general rule of thumb, the fianchetto is always reasonable in case White is not super ambitious or aggressive in the center. Typically when White has played d3, this is a good sign that we can afford playing the fianchetto without getting checkmated (at least not instantly).I've also tried the principled approach of going3...e54.Ngf3Bd65.g3, but my feeling is that with best play the positions are pretty equal, while generally your opponents will be knowing this stuff way better since it's Black's main line.To this, add the fact that they also gain the option of playing3...e54.Ngf3Bd6and now5.d4!?, and Black needs to be quite precise not to get in really big trouble from the opening.In conclusion: with3...g6we are going to achieve an equal game while counting on the fact that our opponent will be less familiar with the fianchetto approach.} 
4. Ngf3
4. Bg7
5. e5 {This move is definitely super rare, but it's worth mentioning since it deviates from our standard game plan where we manage to push ...e5!} 
5. c5 {This key move puts White's set-up under a pretty big question mark. We are ready to follow up with the typical ...Nc6-Bg4 and White will have a hard time protecting the e5-pawn.} 
6. c3
6. Nc6
7. d4
7. cxd4
8. cxd4
8. Qb6
9. Nb3
9. Bg4 {Threatening ...Bxf3 which would force White to ruin their pawn structure to keep d4 protected.} 
10. Be2
10. Nh6 {We are ready to play ...Nf5 on the next move and White should seriously watch out for the d4-pawn.} 
