3. g6 {Once again, we are deviating from the most common path. As a general rule of thumb, the fianchetto is always reasonable in case White is not super ambitious or aggressive in the center. Typically when White has played d3, this is a good sign that we can afford playing the fianchetto without getting checkmated (at least not instantly).I've also tried the principled approach of going3...e54.Ngf3Bd65.g3, but my feeling is that with best play the positions are pretty equal, while generally your opponents will be knowing this stuff way better since it's Black's main line.To this, add the fact that they also gain the option of playing3...e54.Ngf3Bd6and now5.d4!?, and Black needs to be quite precise not to get in really big trouble from the opening.In conclusion: with3...g6we are going to achieve an equal game while counting on the fact that our opponent will be less familiar with the fianchetto approach.} 
4. Ngf3
4. Bg7
5. g3 {This is by far the main move and what I expect you to face the most after White decides to play the King's Indian Attack.} 
5. Nh6 {This move is the complete opposite of what you are taught in chess elementary school (which is perhaps why I decided to recommend it). By placing the knight on the edge, we are actually sidestepping ideas such as5...Nf6when sooner or later White could expand in the center by pushing e5! Also, please keep in mind that the knight will not stay on h6 forever, and we are going to play ...f6-Nf7 later).} 
6. Bg2
6. O-O
7. O-O
7. e5 {Not only have we managed to avoid White's e5-push, but we also get our fair share of the center.} 
8. Re1 {This is really White's main move. Everything else will generally transpose to what we are going to see in the following moves.} 
8. f6 {Placing the knight on the rim and then going ...f6?! 'What is this guy's course about, we should probably check out some stuff on chessly at this point...' You definitely should because Levy is a great guy! But jokes aside, Black is preparing to play ...Nf7 and this plan is just incredibly powerful even I was surprised.} 
9. c3 {This is the most common move for online games.9.d4This aggressive looking move does not really do much harm.9...Nf7With a solid position for Black, threatening to push ...f5 in case White does nothing.10.exd5cxd511.dxe5fxe512.c4?!Double trading pawns in the center followed by this break seems to be very common online for some reason.12...e4!13.Nh4g5-+Simply trapping the h4-knight.} 
9. Nf7 {If White does nothing, we are ready to expand on the kingside with ...f5!} 
10. d4 {This is the only somewhat challenging move.10.exd5For some reason the following sequence is pretty common for online games.10...cxd511.d4??e412.Nh4g5-+Trapping White's knight.} 
10. a5 {Taking space on the queenside while preparing the standard ...Na6-Nc7 maneuver.} 
11. a4
11. Na6
12. b3
12. Be6
13. Ba3
13. Re8 {With a balanced position. Keep in mind that Black is having ideas such as ...dxe4 followed by ...f5-e4!, which could be quite problematic for White to deal with.} 
