1. c6 {In this chapter we will consider the most ridiculous lines that you are probably facing regularly below 1400 (and at times, some actual interesting sidelines).} 
2. Nc3 {2.f4This is super common especially below 1500.2...d53.e5c5!The key to maximize your results against 2.f4 is to treat it exactly like we are facing the 'Advance Variation'.4.Nf3Nc65.Bb5Bg4=We will continue with ...e6-Ne7-Nf5 while always meeting h3 with . ..Bxf3! exactly like against the 'Advance Variation'.2.Bc4Here we have your favorite opening to face, the Hillbilly Attack! This is nothing really special, it just gives Black an improved version of the 'Exchange Variation', so make sure to master that chapter first if you are willing to really start crushing this weird opening!2...d53.exd5cxd54.Bb5+This is common amongst beginners from a number of move orders.4...Bd7!While there is nothing wrong with 4...Nc6, trading bishops is way easier from my experience.5.Bxd7+Nxd7=I noticed this move scores even better than 5...Qxd7! Black is going to finish development with ...Ngf6-e6-Bd6 followed by ...O-O and then play on the queenside wtih ...b5 (using the minority attack).2.b3The Euwe Attack! This romantic approach leads to a better game for Black with correct play.2...d53.Bb2White's idea is to gambit the pawn and hope for long-term compensation.3...dxe44.Nc3Nf65.Qe2Bf5⩱We are going to continue with ...e6-Nbd7 followed by ...Qa5-Ba3 ideas while any h3-g4 ideas by White will be immediately stopped with ...h5!2.d4d53.Nc3dxe44.f3The so called 'Rasa-Studier Gambit'. This of course resembles the more popular 'Blackmar-Diemer Gambit'.4...e5⇆While there is nothing wrong with accepting the gambit, I think this move just kills all the fun for White before it even begins!} 
2. d5
3. Qe2 {This sideline gave me the most headache out of them all. The tricky part is that if you are going for the ambitious 3...d4, the upcoming positions are tough to evaluate and the computer can give you a false sense of safety in this King's Indian type of position.3.Qf3Similar to 3.Qe2, this variation is super rare. The difference is that White is now threatening to win a pawn on d5.3...dxe44.Nxe4Nf6!In case White takes on f6, Black just gets an improved Tartakower because the f3-queen is not ideally placed.5.Bc4Nbd7!Creating a big positional threat of ... Ne5!6.d4Nb6⇆White is left with a very tricky situation having to protect both the c4-bishop and the d4-pawn!3.f4This variation is pretty common for lower rated players.3...dxe44.Nxe4Nf6=Black just gets an improved version of the Tartakower because the f4-pawn is not particulary helpful.} 
3. dxe4 {Objectively this is a bit inferior compared to3...d4, but I think3...dxe4is way more practical.} 
4. Nxe4
4. Nf6 {Here we get bit of an unusual version of the Tartakower, but with White's queen placed on e2, this definitely makes sense.} 
5. Nxf6+
5. gxf6
6. Nf3
6. c5 {We are going to continue with ...Nc6-e5 followed by ...Be6-Qd7 and ...O-O-O.} 
