1. e4
1. c6
2. f4 {This is one of the sidelines that I expect you to face the most (especially below 1500). I would classify this simply as an improved version of the 'Advance Variation' for Black, because it's not obvious that White really needs to play f4, while we can get the standard development.} 
2. d5
3. e5
3. c5 {If you remember to play this move, you will generally be ok. The critical idea to remember is that we want to play ...Nc6 and get the move ...Bg4 in if possible, with very similar play to what we've seen in the 'Advance Variation'.From my experience, most new Caro-Kann players rush with3...Bf5, which is not a bad move in itself, but it is entering slightly different teritory compared to what we are generally used to.} 
4. Nf3
4. Nc6
5. Bb5 {This is the most popular move for White in online games.5.c3This move is generally played to push d4 (hoping to get a massive center).5...Bg46.Be2e67.O-ONge78.d4Nf5Creating a big threat of ...Bxf3 followed by ...cxd4 (winning a pawn).9.dxc5Bxc5+10.Kh1h5∓There is also nothing wrong with10...O-O, but10...h5could win you so many games in a matter of seconds! The point is to play ...h4 followed by ...Ng3+! and White is getting brutally checkmated along the h-file.} 
5. Bg4
6. Bxc6+ {Players who go for 5.Bb5 generally will follow it up by taking on c6.} 
6. bxc6
7. O-O
7. e6
8. h3
8. Bxf3 {Remember that we see this variation as an improved version of the 'Advance', where typically we always meet h3 by going ...Bxf3 (fighting for control over the d4-square).} 
9. Qxf3
9. Ne7
10. d3
10. Nf5
11. g4 {This move may look very appealing to 'coffee-house' players, but it can definitely backfire if countered properly.11.Nc3h5!This is an important move to keep White's kingside play under control. It comes with a positional threat of pushing ...h4, which fixes the situation completely, and then Black has nothing to worry about.12.Ne2h4⩱We can finish development by going ...Be7 and ...O-O, followed by queenside pressure connected with moves such as ...a5-a4 (fixing the b2-pawn) + ...Qb6-Rfb8.} 
11. Nh4
12. Qg3
12. h5 {This move should always be on your radar when White is playing this aggressively while having the king on the same side. In general, the Caro-Kann is more of a strategic opening, but if White is asking for trouble, there is no need to be shy!The way you can visualize this whole situation is basically like this: -imagine you just followed a girl on instagram and you try your shot by liking her most recent 3 posts and she does the same thing (hard to believe, I know). In this scenario it might be pretty safe to send a text! (I charge double for my dating advice.)} 
